{"title_page": "Michel DeGraff", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Michel Degraff\n| honorific_suffix =\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = Michel Degraff at MIT.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = Degraff at M.I.T. \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = [[Haiti]]\n| death_date        = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place       =     \n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names       = \n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = [[Linguistics]] [[Syntax]] Morphology [[Language Change]] [[Creole Studies]] [[Haitian Creole]], [[Education in Haiti]] [[Linguistics-Ideology Interface]]\n| workplaces        = [[M.I.T.]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| thesis_title      = Creole grammars and acquisition of syntax: The case of Haitian\n| thesis_url        = http://repository.upenn.edu/dissertations/AAI9308555\n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = {{Plainlist|\n* Arguing  that Haitian Creole is a full-fledged language\n* Advocacy for the language of instruction in Haiti to be Haitian Creole\n}}\n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = [[National Science Foundation]] $1 Million Grant to promote teaching of Science in Haiti in Haitian Creole\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse            = \n| children          = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = {{URL|http://web.mit.edu/linguistics/people/faculty/degraff/index.html}}\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Michel Frederic DeGraff'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lenouvelliste.com/lenouvelliste/article/138941/les-33-academiciens-du-creole-haitien-investis-dans-leur-fonction |title=Les 33 acad\u00e9miciens du cr\u00e9ole ha\u00eftien investis dans leur fonction |editor=Merc\u00e9us, Bertrand |date=4 December 2014 |publisher=Le NOuvelliste |accessdate=22 June 2016}} {{in lang|fr}}</ref> is a Haitian [[Creolistics|creolist]] who has served on the board of the ''Journal of Haitian Studies''.<ref name=\"zephir\">{{cite journal|last1=Z\u00e9phir|first1=Flore |authorlink=Flore Z\u00e9phir |title=Creolist Michel Degraff: A profile of Commitment, Advocacy, Excellence and Hope|journal=Journal of Haitian Studies|date=Fall 2012|volume=18|issue=2|page=268}}</ref> He is a tenured professor at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]<ref name=\"zephir\" /> and a founding member of the [[Haitian Creole Academy]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Michel DeGraff named charter member of the Haitian Creole Academy|url = http://whamit.mit.edu/2014/12/15/michel-degraff-becomes-member-of-the-haitian-creole-academy/|website = Whamit!|accessdate = 2015-11-02}}</ref>  His field of scholarship is [[Creole language]], also known as ''Lang Krey\u00f2l'' Linguistics.<ref name=\"zephir\" /> He is known for his advocacy towards the recognition of [[Haitian Creole]] as a full-fledged language.<ref name=\"zephir\" /> In the fall of 2012, he received a $1 million grant from the [[National Science Foundation]] to introduce online Creole language materials in the teaching of [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] in Haiti.<ref name=\"zephir\" /> He believes that Haitian children should be taught in their native language at all levels of instruction, contrary to the tradition of teaching them in French. <ref name=VFH>{{cite web|last1=Ulysse|first1=Katia|title=Michel Degraff: Our Word is Our Bond|url=http://www.voicesfromhaiti.com/inner-views/michel-degraff-mit-linguistics-professor-our-word-is-our-bond/|website=Voices from Ha\u00efti|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Degraff believes that instruction in French, a foreign language for most Haitian children, hinders their creativity and their ability to excel.<ref name=VFH></ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAs a child growing up in a middle-class Haitian family and attending a top school where the instruction was in [[French language|French]], Degraff reports that despite being a top student, he often felt that French was a hindrance as not speaking it well caused complexes of inferiority among otherwise bright children.<ref name=VFH></ref> He remembers believing that he spoke one and half language, [[Haitian Creole]] being the \"half\", when in fact the language that all children spoke well by default was Creole. <ref name=VFH></ref> He recalls that French, although imposed at home and at school, was never used for jokes or on the soccer field. <ref name=VFH></ref>\n\n==Education==\nDr. DeGraff holds a PhD in computer science from the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"dizikes\">{{cite web|last1=Dizikes|first1=Peter|title=A Champion of Creole|url=http://newsoffice.mit.edu/2011/profile-degraff-0512|publisher=MIT|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref> Prior to his PhD, he studied computer science at [[City College of New York]].<ref name=\"dizikes\" /> He arrived at City College from Haiti in 1982.<ref name=\"dizikes\" /> He developed an interest in linguistics during an internship at [[Bell Labs]] in [[New Jersey]] in 1985.<ref name=\"dizikes\" />\n\n==Work in Haiti==\nDr. Degraff currently works with introducing ICT to Haitian children being instructed in Creole at the Mat\u00e8nwa school in La Gon\u00e2ve.  The children are encouraged to use Google Translate to read what is available on the web in languages other than Creole. With a National Science Foundation grant, he is also using computer games in Creole to teach them math skills. <ref name=VFH></ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See Also==\n* [[Akademi Krey\u00f2l Ayisyen]]\n\n==External Links==\n\n* [http://mit-ayiti.net/ Platf\u00f2m MIT-Ayiti] Open access repository of Creole teaching materials \n* [http://linguistics.mit.edu/user/degraff/ Official Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n\n<br />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DeGraff, Michel}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Haitian academics]]\n[[Category:Linguists of pidgins and creoles]]\n[[Category:City College of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Computational linguistics]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Haiti-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Michel Degraff\n| honorific_suffix =\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = Michel Degraff at MIT.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = Degraff at M.I.T. \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = [[Haiti]]\n| death_date        = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place       =     \n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names       = \n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = [[Linguistics]] [[Syntax]] Morphology [[Language Change]] [[Creole Studies]] [[Haitian Creole]], [[Education in Haiti]] [[Linguistics-Ideology Interface]]\n| workplaces        = [[M.I.T.]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| thesis_title      = Creole grammars and acquisition of syntax: The case of Haitian\n| thesis_url        = http://repository.upenn.edu/dissertations/AAI9308555\n| thesis_year       = \n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = {{Plainlist|\n* Arguing  that Haitian Creole is a full-fledged language\n* Advocacy for the language of instruction in Haiti to be Haitian Creole\n}}\n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = [[National Science Foundation]] $1 Million Grant to promote teaching of Science in Haiti in Haitian Creole\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse            = \n| children          = \n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = {{URL|http://web.mit.edu/linguistics/people/faculty/degraff/index.html}}\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Michel Frederic DeGraff'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lenouvelliste.com/lenouvelliste/article/138941/les-33-academiciens-du-creole-haitien-investis-dans-leur-fonction |title=Les 33 acad\u00e9miciens du cr\u00e9ole ha\u00eftien investis dans leur fonction |editor=Merc\u00e9us, Bertrand |date=4 December 2014 |publisher=Le NOuvelliste |accessdate=22 June 2016}} {{in lang|fr}}</ref> is a Haitian [[Creolistics|creolist]] who has served on the board of the ''Journal of Haitian Studies''.<ref name=\"zephir\">{{cite journal|last1=Z\u00e9phir|first1=Flore |authorlink=Flore Z\u00e9phir |title=Creolist Michel Degraff: A profile of Commitment, Advocacy, Excellence and Hope|journal=Journal of Haitian Studies|date=Fall 2012|volume=18|issue=2|page=268}}</ref> He is a tenured professor at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]<ref name=\"zephir\" /> and a founding member of the [[Haitian Creole Academy]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Michel DeGraff named charter member of the Haitian Creole Academy|url = http://whamit.mit.edu/2014/12/15/michel-degraff-becomes-member-of-the-haitian-creole-academy/|website = Whamit!|accessdate = 2015-11-02}}</ref>  His field of scholarship is [[Creole language]], also known as ''Lang Krey\u00f2l'' Linguistics.<ref name=\"zephir\" /> He is known for his advocacy towards the recognition of [[Haitian Creole]] as a full-fledged language.<ref name=\"zephir\" /> In the fall of 2012, he received a $1 million grant from the [[National Science Foundation]] to introduce online Creole language materials in the teaching of [[Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics|STEM]] in Haiti.<ref name=\"zephir\" /> He believes that Haitian children should be taught in their native language at all levels of instruction, contrary to the tradition of teaching them in French. <ref name=VFH>{{cite web|last1=Ulysse|first1=Katia|title=Michel Degraff: Our Word is Our Bond|url=http://www.voicesfromhaiti.com/inner-views/michel-degraff-mit-linguistics-professor-our-word-is-our-bond/|website=Voices from Ha\u00efti|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref> Degraff believes that instruction in French, a foreign language for most Haitian children, hinders their creativity and their ability to excel.<ref name=VFH></ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAs a child growing up in a middle-class Haitian family and attending a top school where the instruction was in [[French language|French]], Degraff reports that despite being a top student, he often felt that French was a hindrance as not speaking it well caused complexes of inferiority among otherwise bright children.<ref name=VFH></ref> He remembers believing that he spoke one and half language, [[Haitian Creole]] being the \"half\", when in fact the language that all children spoke well by default was Creole. <ref name=VFH></ref> He recalls that French, although imposed at home and at school, was never used for jokes or on the soccer field. <ref name=VFH></ref>\n\n==Education==\nDr. DeGraff holds a PhD in computer science from the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"dizikes\">{{cite web|last1=Dizikes|first1=Peter|title=A Champion of Creole|url=http://newsoffice.mit.edu/2011/profile-degraff-0512|publisher=MIT|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref> Prior to his PhD, he studied computer science at [[City College of New York]].<ref name=\"dizikes\" /> He arrived at City College from Haiti in 1982.<ref name=\"dizikes\" /> He developed an interest in linguistics during an internship at [[Bell Labs]] in [[New Jersey]] in 1985.<ref name=\"dizikes\" />\n\n==Work in Haiti==\nDr. Degraff currently works with introducing ICT to Haitian children being instructed in Creole at the Mat\u00e8nwa school in La Gon\u00e2ve.  The children are encouraged to use Google Translate to read what is available on the web in languages other than Creole. With a National Science Foundation grant, he is also using computer games in Creole to teach them math skills. <ref name=VFH></ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See Also==\n* [[Akademi Krey\u00f2l Ayisyen]]\n\n==External Links==\n\n* [http://mit-ayiti.net/ Platf\u00f2m MIT-Ayiti] Open access repository of Creole teaching materials \n* [http://linguistics.mit.edu/user/degraff/ Official Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n\n\n<br />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DeGraff, Michel}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Haitian academics]]\n[[Category:Linguists of pidgins and creoles]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:Computational linguistics]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Haiti-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Inter&anthro", "label": "safe", "comment": "mentioned and sourced in the article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michel_DeGraff"}
{"title_page": "Duke of la Alcudia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox nobility title\n| name              = Dukedom of la Alcudia \n| image             = [[Image:COA Duke of Sueca.svg|150px]] \n| image_size        =  \n| alt               =  \n| caption           = \n| creation_date     = 4 July 1792 \n| creation          =  \n| monarch           = [[Charles IV of Spain]] \n| peerage           = [[Spanish nobility]] \n| baronetage        =  \n| first_holder      = [[Manuel Godoy]] and \u00c1lvarez de Far\u00eda \n| last_holder       =  \n| present_holder    = [[Carlos Ruspoli, 7th Duke of Alcudia]] \n| heir_apparent     = \n| heir_presumptive  =  \n| remainder_to      = the 1st Duke's [[heirs]] lawfully begotten. For his marriage with [[Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n, 15th Countess of Chinch\u00f3n|the daughter]] of the [[Luis of Spain, Count of Chinch\u00f3n|Infante don Luis]] \n| subsidiary_titles = \n| status            =  \n| extinction_date   =  \n| family_seat       = [[Palace of Infante don Luis (Boadilla del Monte)|Palace of Infante don Luis]] \n| former_seat       =  \n| motto             =  \n| footnotes         =  \n}}\n\n'''Duke of la Alcudia'''<!--the correct Spanish spelling is Alcudia, not Alc\u00fadia--> (Spanish: ''Duque de la Alcudia'') is a title of [[Spanish nobility]], [[Grandee]] of Spain 1st class. It was created by King [[Charles&nbsp;IV of Spain]] in 1792 for [[Manuel Godoy]], who was the [[List of Prime Ministers of Spain|Prime Minister of Spain]] from 1792 to 1797 and from 1801 to 1808. Its name refers to the ''[[:es:Valle de Alcudia|Valle de Alcudia]]'' in the [[Province of Ciudad Real]] in Spain.\n\n==Manuel Godoy==\n[[File:Agustin Esteve y Marqu\u00e9s - Manuel Godoy - 1954.312 - Art Institute of Chicago.jpg|thumb|300x300px|[[Manuel Godoy]], Prince of the Peace, 1st Duke of la Alcudia, 1st Duke of Sueca, Count of \u00c9voramonte, Baron of Mascalb\u00f3, Prime Minister of [[Charles&nbsp;IV of Spain]]]]\nKing Charles IV also granted to Manuel Godoy the Duchy of Sueca, the Barony of Mascalb\u00f3 and the title of Prince of the Peace. The granting of the latter was an exception in Spanish noble history; since the Middle Ages, no one had held the princely dignity in Spain except the heir of the crown, who did so through three titles: [[Prince of Asturias]], Gerona and of Viana. \n\nHe was granted the Portuguese county of \u00c9voramonte, which was due to his marriage to the [[Countess of Chinch\u00f3n]]. However, he was exiled in 1808 when Spain came under [[Kingdom of Spain under Joseph Bonaparte|Bonaparte rule]], and he was not authorized to return to Spain until 1844. \n\nGodoy was also, by papal concession, Prince of Bassano, a title he obtained after acquiring the Italian fief of Bassano di Sutri, located between Rome and Viterbo, during his long exile in Rome.\n\nIt seems that he was also \"Marqu\u00e9s de \u00c1lvarez\", as it is named in different documents, although it is a title that was never used by his successors, nor has anyone attempted to rehabilitate it, nor is it stated in the Cast of Greatness and Titles Nobiliarios Espa\u00f1oles or in the Directory of the ''Diputaci\u00f3n de la Grandeza''. He was also \"Lord of Soto of Rome\" and \"Viscount of High Andalusia\".\n\n== Title holders ==\n# [[Manuel Godoy|Manuel Godoy y \u00c1lvarez de Faria]] (1792\u20131851)\n# [[Adolfo Ruspoli, 2nd Duke of Alcudia|Adolfo Ruspoli y Godoy]] (1853\u20131914)\n#[[Carlos Ruspoli, 3rd Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos Ruspoli y \u00c1lvarez de Toledo]] (1915\u20131936)\n#[[Camilo Ruspoli, 4th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Camilo Carlos Ruspoli y Caro]] (1951\u20131958)\n#[[Carlos Ruspoli, 5th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos Oswaldo Ruspoli y Moren\u00e9s]] (1958\u20132016)\n#[[Luis Carlos Ruspoli, 6th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Luis Carlos Ruspoli y S\u00e1nchiz]] (2016-2019)\n#[[Carlos Ruspoli, 7th Duke of Alcudia|Carlos Ruspoli y Alvarez de las \u00c1lvarez de las Asturias Bohorques]] (2019)\n\n== Family tree ==\n[[File:Manuel Godoy Escudo.jpg|thumb|Coat of arms of Manuel Godoy|360x360px]]\n<center>\n<div align=\"center\" style=\"padding: 0.5em; font-size:90%;\">{{familytree/start}}\n{{familytree |NMAI|NMAI=[[Manuel Godoy]] and \u00c1lvarez de Faria,<br>I Duke of la Alcudia and Sueca<br><small>(1767\u20131851)</small>|estilocaja_NMAI =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree | |!| |}}\n{{familytree |NMAI|NMAI=[[Carlota de Godoy, 2nd Duchess of Sueca|Carlota de Godoy and Borb\u00f3n,<br>II Duchess of Sueca]]<br><small>(1800\u20131886)</small>}}\n{{familytree | |!| |}}\n{{familytree |NMAI|NMAI=[[Adolfo Ruspoli, 2nd Duke of Alcudia|Adolfo Ruspoli and Godoy,<br>II Duke of la Alcudia]]<br><small>(1822\u20131914)</small>|estilocaja_NMAI =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree | |!| |}}\n{{familytree |NMAI|NMAI=[[Carlos Ruspoli, 3rd Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos Ruspoli and \u00c1lvarez de Toledo,<br>III Duke of la Alcudia and Sueca]]<br><small>(1858\u20131936)</small>|estilocaja_NMAI =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree | |!| |}}\n{{familytree |NMAI|NMAI=[[Camilo Ruspoli, 4th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos Ruspoli and Caro,<br>IV Duke of la Alcudia and Sueca]]<br><small>(1904\u20131975)</small>|estilocaja_NMAI =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree | |)|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{familytree |a| | |ba|a=[[Carlos Ruspoli, 5th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos Ruspoli and Moren\u00e9s,<br />V Duke of Alcudia and Sueca,<br />XIX Count of Chinch\u00f3n]]<br /><small>(1932\u20132016)</small>|estilocaja_a =background-color:#CCCCFF|ba=[[Luis Ruspoli, 7th Marquis of Boadilla del Monte|Luis Ruspoli and Moren\u00e9s,<br />VII Marquis of Boadilla del Monte]]<br /><small>(1933\u20132011)</small>|estilocaja_ba =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree | | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree | | | | | |a|a=[[Luis Carlos Ruspoli, 6th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Luis Ruspoli and S\u00e1nchiz,<br />VI Duke of Alcudia and Sueca,<br />XX Count of Chinch\u00f3n]]<br /><small>(2016)</small>|estilocaja_a =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree/end}}\n</center>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of current Grandees of Spain]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Elenco de Grandezas y T\u00edtulos Espa\u00f1oles. Instituto \"Salazar y Castro\" C.S.I.C.\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dukedom of Alcudia}}\n[[Category:Dukes of Alcudia| ]]\n[[Category:Dukedoms of Spain]]\n[[Category:Grandees of Spain]]\n[[Category:Lists of dukes|Alcudia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox nobility title\n| name              = Dukedom of la Alcudia \n| image             = [[Image:COA Duke of Sueca.svg|150px]] \n| image_size        =  \n| alt               =  \n| caption           = \n| creation_date     = 4 July 1792 \n| creation          =  \n| monarch           = [[Charles IV of Spain]] \n| peerage           = [[Spanish nobility]] \n| baronetage        =  \n| first_holder      = [[Manuel Godoy]] and \u00c1lvarez de Far\u00eda \n| last_holder       =  \n| present_holder    = [[Carlos Ruspoli, 7th Duke of Alcudia]] \n| heir_apparent     = \n| heir_presumptive  =  \n| remainder_to      = the 1st Duke's [[heirs]] lawfully begotten. For his marriage with [[Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n, 15th Countess of Chinch\u00f3n|the daughter]] of the [[Luis of Spain, Count of Chinch\u00f3n|Infante don Luis]] \n| subsidiary_titles = \n| status            =  \n| extinction_date   =  \n| family_seat       = [[Palace of Infante don Luis (Boadilla del Monte)|Palace of Infante don Luis]] \n| former_seat       =  \n| motto             =  \n| footnotes         =  \n}}\n\n'''Duke of la Alcudia'''<!--the correct Spanish spelling is Alcudia, not Alc\u00fadia--> (Spanish: ''Duque de la Alcudia'') is a title of [[Spanish nobility]], [[Grandee]] of Spain 1st class. It was created by King [[Charles&nbsp;IV of Spain]] in 1792 for [[Manuel Godoy]], who was the [[List of Prime Ministers of Spain|Prime Minister of Spain]] from 1792 to 1797 and from 1801 to 1808. Its name refers to the ''[[:es:Valle de Alcudia|Valle de Alcudia]]'' in the [[Province of Ciudad Real]] in Spain.\n\n==Manuel Godoy==\n[[File:Agustin Esteve y Marqu\u00e9s - Manuel Godoy - 1954.312 - Art Institute of Chicago.jpg|thumb|300x300px|[[Manuel Godoy]], Prince of the Peace, 1st Duke of la Alcudia, 1st Duke of Sueca, Count of \u00c9voramonte, Baron of Mascalb\u00f3, Prime Minister of [[Charles&nbsp;IV of Spain]]]]\nKing Charles IV also granted to Manuel Godoy the Duchy of Sueca, the Barony of Mascalb\u00f3 and the title of Prince of the Peace. The granting of the latter was an exception in Spanish noble history; since the Middle Ages, no one had held the princely dignity in Spain except the heir of the crown, who did so through three titles: [[Prince of Asturias]], Gerona and of Viana. \n\nHe was granted the Portuguese county of \u00c9voramonte, which was due to his marriage to the [[Countess of Chinch\u00f3n]]. However, he was exiled in 1808 when Spain came under [[Kingdom of Spain under Joseph Bonaparte|Bonaparte rule]], and he was not authorized to return to Spain until 1844. \n\nGodoy was also, by papal concession, Prince of Bassano, a title he obtained after acquiring the Italian fief of Bassano di Sutri, located between Rome and Viterbo, during his long exile in Rome.\n\nIt seems that he was also \"Marqu\u00e9s de \u00c1lvarez\", as it is named in different documents, although it is a title that was never used by his successors, nor has anyone attempted to rehabilitate it, nor is it stated in the Cast of Greatness and Titles Nobiliarios Espa\u00f1oles or in the Directory of the ''Diputaci\u00f3n de la Grandeza''. He was also \"Lord of Soto of Rome\" and \"Viscount of High Andalusia\".\n\n== Title holders ==\n# [[Manuel Godoy|Manuel Godoy y \u00c1lvarez de Faria]] (1792\u20131851)\n# [[Adolfo Ruspoli, 2nd Duke of Alcudia|Adolfo Ruspoli y Godoy]] (1853\u20131914)\n#[[Carlos Ruspoli, 3rd Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos Ruspoli y \u00c1lvarez de Toledo]] (1915\u20131936)\n#[[Camilo Ruspoli, 4th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Camilo Carlos Ruspoli y Caro]] (1951\u20131958)\n#[[Carlos Ruspoli, 5th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos Oswaldo Ruspoli y Moren\u00e9s]] (1958\u20132016)\n#[[Luis Carlos Ruspoli, 6th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Luis Carlos Ruspoli y S\u00e1nchiz]] (2016-2019)\n#[[Carlos Ruspoli, 7th Duke of Alcudia|Carlos Ruspoli y Alvarez de las \u00c1lvarez de las Asturias Bohorques]] (2019)\n\n== History of the dukes ==\n'''I Duke: '''[[Manuel Godoy]], I Duke of la Alcudia, and later, I [[:es:Ducado de Sueca|Duke of Sueca]] and I [[:es:Baron\u00eda de Mascalb\u00f3|Baron of Mascalb\u00f3]]. He also received the title of [[:es:Principado de la Paz|Prince of the Peace]] (which was expropriated by King Ferdinand&nbsp;VII in 1808), [[:es:Principado de Bassano|Prince of Bassano]] (pontifical), and I [[:es:Condado de \u00c9voramonte|Count of \u00c9voramonte]] (Portuguese title). He married: [[Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n, 15th Countess of Chinch\u00f3n|Do\u00f1a Mar\u00eda Teresa de Borb\u00f3n y Vallabriga]], XV [[Count of Chinch\u00f3n|Countess of Chinch\u00f3n]], who was the eldest daughter of the [[Luis of Spain, Count of Chinch\u00f3n|Cardinal-Infante Don Luis de Borb\u00f3n y Farnesio]]. The first duke's grandson succeeded him:\n\n'''II Duke:''' [[Adolfo Ruspoli, 2nd Duke of Alcudia|Adolfo Ruspoli y Godoy, Khevenhueller-Metsch and Bourbon]] (1822\u20131914), II Duke of la Alcudia, [[Grandeza de Espa\u00f1a|Grandee of Spain 1st class]] and III Count of \u00c9voramonte, in Portugal. He married in 1857 with Rosal\u00eda \u00c1lvarez de Toledo y Silva, daughter of the [[Duke of Medina Sidonia]]. His son succeeded him:\n\n'''III Duke:''' [[Carlos Ruspoli, 3rd Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos R\u00faspoli y \u00c1lvarez de Toledo, Godoy and Silva-Baz\u00e1n]] (1858\u20131936), III Duke of la Alcudia, III Duke of Sueca, XVII [[Count of Chinch\u00f3n]], IV Count of \u00c9voramonte, in Portugal. [[Grandes de Espa\u00f1a|Grandee of Spain 1st class]]. He married Carmen Caro and Caro, of the Marquesses of the Romana. His son succeeded him:\n\n'''IV Duke:''' [[Camilo Ruspoli, 4th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Camilo R\u00faspoli y Caro, \u00c1lvarez de Toledo and Caro]] (1904\u20131975), who reunites all the titles, both of Manuel Godoy, and of the Infanta Mar\u00eda Teresa, by which he became the IV Duke of la Alcudia, IV Duke of Sueca, XVIII Count of Chinch\u00f3n, and VI [[Boadilla del Monte|Marquess of Boadilla del Monte]]. [[Grandeza de Espa\u00f1a|Grandee of Spain 1st class]]. He married Bel\u00e9n Moren\u00e9s and Arteaga, XVIII Countess of Ba\u00f1ares. His son succeeded him:\n\n'''V Duke''': [[Carlos Ruspoli, 5th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos R\u00faspoli y Moren\u00e9s, Caro and Arteaga]] (1932\u20132016), V Duke of la Alcudia, V Duke of Sueca, XIX Count of Chinch\u00f3n. [[Grandeza de Espa\u00f1a|Grandee of Spain 1st class]]. Without issue. His nephew succeeded him:\n\n'''VI Duke''': [[Luis Carlos Ruspoli, 6th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Luis Ruspoli and S\u00e1nchiz, Moren\u00e9s and N\u00fa\u00f1ez-Robres]] (1963), VI Duke of la Alcudia, VI Duke of Sueca, XX Count of Chinch\u00f3n. [[Grandeza de Espa\u00f1a|Grandee of Spain 1st class]]. VIII Marquis of Boadilla del Monte and III Baron of Mascalb\u00f3. He married Mar\u00eda \u00c1lvarez de las Asturias Bohorques and Rumeu, of the [[Duke of Gor|Dukes of Gor]].\n\n== Family tree ==\n[[File:Manuel Godoy Escudo.jpg|thumb|Coat of arms of Manuel Godoy|360x360px]]\n<center>\n<div align=\"center\" style=\"padding: 0.5em; font-size:90%;\">{{familytree/start}}\n{{familytree |NMAI|NMAI=[[Manuel Godoy]] and \u00c1lvarez de Faria,<br>I Duke of la Alcudia and Sueca<br><small>(1767\u20131851)</small>|estilocaja_NMAI =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree | |!| |}}\n{{familytree |NMAI|NMAI=[[Carlota de Godoy, 2nd Duchess of Sueca|Carlota de Godoy and Borb\u00f3n,<br>II Duchess of Sueca]]<br><small>(1800\u20131886)</small>}}\n{{familytree | |!| |}}\n{{familytree |NMAI|NMAI=[[Adolfo Ruspoli, 2nd Duke of Alcudia|Adolfo Ruspoli and Godoy,<br>II Duke of la Alcudia]]<br><small>(1822\u20131914)</small>|estilocaja_NMAI =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree | |!| |}}\n{{familytree |NMAI|NMAI=[[Carlos Ruspoli, 3rd Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos Ruspoli and \u00c1lvarez de Toledo,<br>III Duke of la Alcudia and Sueca]]<br><small>(1858\u20131936)</small>|estilocaja_NMAI =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree | |!| |}}\n{{familytree |NMAI|NMAI=[[Camilo Ruspoli, 4th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos Ruspoli and Caro,<br>IV Duke of la Alcudia and Sueca]]<br><small>(1904\u20131975)</small>|estilocaja_NMAI =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree | |)|-|-|-|.|}}\n{{familytree |a| | |ba|a=[[Carlos Ruspoli, 5th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Carlos Ruspoli and Moren\u00e9s,<br />V Duke of Alcudia and Sueca,<br />XIX Count of Chinch\u00f3n]]<br /><small>(1932\u20132016)</small>|estilocaja_a =background-color:#CCCCFF|ba=[[Luis Ruspoli, 7th Marquis of Boadilla del Monte|Luis Ruspoli and Moren\u00e9s,<br />VII Marquis of Boadilla del Monte]]<br /><small>(1933\u20132011)</small>|estilocaja_ba =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree | | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree | | | | | |a|a=[[Luis Carlos Ruspoli, 6th Duke of Alcudia and Sueca|Luis Ruspoli and S\u00e1nchiz,<br />VI Duke of Alcudia and Sueca,<br />XX Count of Chinch\u00f3n]]<br /><small>(2016)</small>|estilocaja_a =background-color:#CCCCFF}}\n{{familytree/end}}\n</center>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of current Grandees of Spain]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Elenco de Grandezas y T\u00edtulos Espa\u00f1oles. Instituto \"Salazar y Castro\" C.S.I.C.\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dukedom of Alcudia}}\n[[Category:Dukes of Alcudia| ]]\n[[Category:Dukedoms of Spain]]\n[[Category:Grandees of Spain]]\n[[Category:Lists of dukes|Alcudia]]\n", "name_user": "37.10.153.109", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duke_of_la_Alcudia"}
{"title_page": "Billy Wease", "text_new": "{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Billy Wease\n| image             = \n| imagesize         = \n| caption           = \n| nationality       = {{flagicon|USA}} American\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1986|10|09}}\n| birth_place       = [[Noblesville, Indiana|Noblesville]], [[Indiana]], U.S.\n| current series    = [[USAC Silver Crown Series]]\n| first year        = 2007\n| current team      = \n| car number        = \n| starts            = 13\n| wins              = 0\n| poles             = 0\n| best finish       = 8th\n| year              = 2007\n| titles            = [[Turkey Night Grand Prix]]\n| title years       = 2006\n| awards            = \n| award years       = \n}}\n'''Billy Wease''' (born October 9, 1986 in [[Noblesville, Indiana]]) is a driver in [[United States Automobile Club|USAC]]. He was a development driver for [[Penske Racing]] in the mid 2000s. Wease was also the 2006 [[Turkey Night Grand Prix]] winner,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/nov/25/sports/sp-newswire25|title=Wease wins at Irwindale; Stewart finishes 24th|last=Herbert|first=Steven|date=November 25, 2006|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=2017-01-13|location=Los Angeles|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113060018/http://articles.latimes.com/2006/nov/25/sports/sp-newswire25|archivedate=2017-01-13}}</ref> and a four-time starter of the [[Anderson Speedway#Little 500|Little 500]].\n\nHe also competed in 2 [[ARCA Racing Series]] races and failed to qualify to one, all of them for [[Penske Racing]]. He best finish was 2nd.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Racing-Reference driver|Billy_Wease}}\n*[http://www.driverdb.com/drivers/14419/ Billy Wease] at DriverDB\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wease, Billy}}\n\n{{Team Penske}} \n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:People from Noblesville, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from Indiana]]\n[[Category:ARCA Menards Series drivers]]\n[[Category:USAC Silver Crown Series drivers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American racing drivers]]\n\n{{US-autoracing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Billy Wease\n| image             = \n| imagesize         = \n| caption           = \n| nationality       = {{flagicon|USA}} American\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1986|10|09}}\n| birth_place       = [[Noblesville, Indiana|Noblesville]], [[Indiana]], U.S.\n| current series    = [[USAC Silver Crown Series]]\n| first year        = 2007\n| current team      = \n| car number        = \n| starts            = 13\n| wins              = 0\n| poles             = 0\n| best finish       = 8th\n| year              = 2007\n| titles            = [[Turkey Night Grand Prix]]\n| title years       = 2006\n| awards            = \n| award years       = \n}}\n'''Billy Wease''' (born October 9, 1986 in [[Noblesville, Indiana]]) is a driver in [[United States Automobile Club|USAC]]. He was a development driver for [[Penske Racing]] in the mid 2000s. Wease was also the 2006 [[Turkey Night Grand Prix]] winner,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/nov/25/sports/sp-newswire25|title=Wease wins at Irwindale; Stewart finishes 24th|last=Herbert|first=Steven|date=November 25, 2006|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=2017-01-13|location=Los Angeles|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113060018/http://articles.latimes.com/2006/nov/25/sports/sp-newswire25|archivedate=2017-01-13}}</ref> and a four-time starter of the [[Anderson Speedway#Little 500|Little 500]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Racing-Reference driver|Billy Wease}}\n*[http://www.driverdb.com/drivers/14419/ Billy Wease] at DriverDB\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wease, Billy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:People from Noblesville, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from Indiana]]\n[[Category:ARCA Menards Series drivers]]\n[[Category:USAC Silver Crown Series drivers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American racing drivers]]\n\n{{US-autoracing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Luks25", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Wease"}
{"title_page": "Ojos del Salado", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name            = Ojos del Salado\n| photo           = Ojos del Salado looming big on the horizon.jpg\n| photo_caption   = The volcano looming on the horizon.\n| elevation_m     = 6893\n| elevation_ref   = <ref name=\"peaklist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peaklist.org/WWlists/ultras/andes1.html|title=Andes ultra-prominent peaks|publisher=Peaklist}}</ref>\n| prominence_m    = 3688\n| prominence_ref  = <ref name=\"peaklist\"/><br/><small>[[List of peaks by prominence|Ranked 44th]]</small>\n| listing         = [[Volcanic Seven Summits]]<br/>[[Seven Second Summits]]<br/>[[List of elevation extremes by country|Country high point]]<br/>[[Ultra-prominent peak|Ultra]]\n| location        = [[Argentina]]\u2013[[Chile]]\n| range           = [[Andes]]\n| map             = Chile\n| map_caption     = Location on the Argentina\u2013Chile border\n| label_position  = left\n| coordinates     = {{coord|27|06|35|S|68|32|29|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = \n| topo            = Highest mountain: Highest Mountain in Chile\n| type            = [[stratovolcano]]\n| age             = \n| last_eruption   = 700 AD \u00b1 300 years<ref name=\"smithsonian\"/>\n| first_ascent    = February 26, 1937 by Jan Alfred Szczepa\u0144ski and Justyn Wojsznis\n| easiest_route   = [[Scrambling|Scramble]]\n}}\n[[File:Volcanic Landscapes, Central Andes labelled.jpg|thumb|350px|Volcanic Landscapes of the Central Andes. Shown are Nevado Ojos del Salado, [[Cerro El C\u00f3ndor]], and [[Peinado]], along the Argentina-Chile border. Astronaut photo from [[International Space Station]], 2010]]\n'''Nevado Ojos del Salado''' is an active [[stratovolcano]] in the [[Andes]] on the [[Argentina]]\u2013[[Chile]] border and the highest active [[volcano]] in the world at {{convert|6893|m|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Axel |last1=Borsdorf |first2=Christoph |last2=Stadel |title=The Andes: A Geographical Portrait |date=March 12, 2015 |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]] |isbn=978-3-319-03530-7 |page=7}}</ref> It is also the second highest mountain in both the [[Western Hemisphere]] and the [[Southern Hemisphere]] behind [[Aconcagua]] at approximately 7,000 meters (22,966 ft) and it is the highest in Chile. Nevado Ojos del Salado is translated to Snowy Salty Eyes describing it being very snowy in the winter and salty with many lakes. \n\nDue to its location near the [[Atacama Desert]], the mountain has very dry conditions, with snow usually only remaining on the peak during winter, though heavy storms can cover the surrounding area with a few feet of snow even in summer. Despite the generally dry conditions, there is a permanent [[Volcanic crater lake|crater lake]] about {{convert|100|m|abbr=on}} in diameter at an elevation of {{convert|6390|m|abbr=on}} on the eastern side of the mountain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andes.org.uk/peak-info-6000/ojos-del-salado-info.asp|title=Andes Website \u2013 Information about Ojos del Salado volcano, a high mountain in South America and the World's highest volcano<!-- Bot generated title -->}}</ref> This is most likely the [[Lake#Notable lakes on Earth|highest lake]] of any kind in the world.\n\nThe ascent of Ojos del Salado is mostly a hike except for the final section to the summit which is a difficult scramble that may require ropes. The first ascent was made in 1937 by [[Jan Alfred Szczepa\u0144ski]] and Justyn Wojsznis, members of a [[Poland|Polish]] expedition in the Andes.\n\nIts name, meaning roughly \"Eyes of the Salty One\" in [[Spanish language|Spanish]], comes from the enormous deposits of salt that, in the form of lagoons or \u201ceyes\u201d, appear in its [[glacier]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.los6000dechile.cl/cumbres_eng/21_ojosdelsalado.html|title=Los 6000 de Chile|publisher=Banco de Chile|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713082419/http://www.los6000dechile.cl/cumbres_eng/21_ojosdelsalado.html|archivedate=July 13, 2007}}</ref> An international highway between Chile and Argentina runs north of the mountain.<ref>Carter 1957, p.242</ref>\n\n==Geology and geomorphology==\n\n=== Regional ===\n\nOjos del Salado along with several other high volcanoes such as [[El Muerto]], [[El Solo]], [[Incahuasi|Nevado Incahuasi]] and [[Nevado Tres Cruces]] lies at the southern end of the [[Central Volcanic Zone]] of the Andes.<ref name=\"Mpodozis 1996, p.539\">Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B, 1996, p.539</ref>\n\nVolcanic activity in the region commenced 26 million years ago in the [[Cordillera Claudio Gay]], at the same time as the neighbouring [[Maricunga Belt]] volcanoes were active. Starting 18 million years ago, local [[subduction]] of the [[Nazca Plate]] beneath the [[South America Plate]] became increasingly shallower and this caused volcanism to shift from the Maricunga Belt to the Ojos del Salado region.<ref name=\"Mpodozis 1996, p.539\"/>\n\nThe [[Paleozoic]] basement crops out only northwest of Nevado Tres Cruces. Other geologic units in the region are [[Oligocene]] sedimentary units and volcanic rocks ranging from Oligocene age to less than 1.5 million years old.<ref>Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B, 1996, p.541</ref> The area is part of a tectonic boundary between a volcanically active region north of the boundary and a less volcanically active region south of the boundary, which is also characterized by geographical differences, e.g. the presence of transverse valleys.<ref>P. E. BAKER, O. GONZALEZ-FERRAN and D. C. REX, 1987 p.85</ref>\n\n=== Local ===\n\nOjos del Salado like other major neighbouring mountains is a complex of [[lava dome]]s and [[lava flow]]s, with the main summit surrounded by peripheral domes such as El Solo and El Fraile<ref>Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B, 1996, p.545</ref> and many other lateral centres.<ref>Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B, 1996, p.546</ref> [[Fumarole]]s are encountered at the summit of Ojos del Salado within a depression.<ref>P. E. BAKER, O. GONZALEZ-FERRAN and D. C. REX, 1987 p.90</ref> [[Potassium-argon dating]] has yielded ages of 1.2 \u00b1 0.3 million years ago and less than 1 million years ago from rocks north of Ojos del Salado.<ref>Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B, 1996, p.542</ref>\n\nThere are [[glacier]]s on the mountain, in the crater and in the form of [[penitente (snow formation)|penitente]]s<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://revistanortegrande.cl/n/14/inventario-de-glaciares-de-los-andes-chilenos-desde-los-18o-a-los-32o-de-latitud-sur/|title=Inventario de glaciares de los Andes chilenos desde los 18\u00ba a los 32\u00ba de latitud sur|date=March 8, 2014|work=Revista Geograf\u00eda Norte Grande|access-date=March 6, 2018|language=es-ES}}</ref> which reach heights of {{convert|8|-|5|m}}.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lliboitry|first1=Louis|title=The Origin of Penitents|journal=Journal of Glaciology|date=1954|volume=2|issue=15|page=334|doi=10.3189/S0022143000025181|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-glaciology/article/div-classtitlethe-origin-of-penitentsdiv/FACAAF8EF9A38B0F14AE85DC6805B8C7|language=en|issn=0022-1430}}</ref> Other reports indicate the absence of glaciers on Ojos del Salado. [[Permafrost]] exists on the mountain and its melting nourishes several lakes; one lake fed by a creek lies at {{convert|6500|m}} altitude.<ref name=\"Aszalos2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Aszal\u00f3s|first1=J\u00falia Margit|last2=Krett|first2=Gergely|last3=Anda|first3=D\u00f3ra|last4=M\u00e1rialigeti|first4=K\u00e1roly|last5=Nagy|first5=Bal\u00e1zs|last6=Borsodi|first6=Andrea K.|title=Diversity of extremophilic bacteria in the sediment of high-altitude lakes located in the mountain desert of Ojos del Salado volcano, Dry-Andes|journal=Extremophiles|date=September 1, 2016|volume=20|issue=5|pages=603\u2013620|doi=10.1007/s00792-016-0849-3|pmid=27315168|language=en|issn=1431-0651}}</ref>\n\nOjos del Salado is an active [[volcano]], but the question of whether it should be considered ''currently'' (or \"historically\") active is arguable. According to the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s [[Global Volcanism Program]],<ref name=\"smithsonian\">{{cite gvp|vnum=1505-13=|title=Ojos del Salado}}</ref> the most recent known eruption was about 1,300 years ago, with a large margin of uncertainty. However, there is also some evidence for a minor ash emission in 1993, which would definitely qualify the volcano as historically active. The presence of [[fumarole]]s high on the mountain and recent-looking [[lava]] flows, albeit of uncertain age, also argues in favor of a categorization as \"active.\"  By these definitions, Ojos del Salado is the highest historically active volcano on Earth. If the older date is accepted, the title of \"highest historically active volcano\" might reside instead with the somewhat lower [[Llullaillaco]] volcano, which certainly has erupted in historic times (most recently in 1877) and is considered active.\n\n===Composition===\nSalado's rock is predominantly [[potassium]]-rich [[dacite]] and [[rhyodacite]]. Its lavas are high in [[biotite]], [[hornblende]], [[plagioclase]], and opaques, with lower levels of [[augite]], quartz, and [[hypersthene]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://volcano.oregonstate.edu/oldroot/CVZ/ojossalado/index.html|title=Nevados Ojos del Salado|publisher=[[Oregon State University]]|work=Volcano World|year=2011|accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Elevation==\nThe elevation of Ojos del Salado has been the subject of debate. The mountain is hidden behind other peaks and thus its height was not appreciated in early research until 1937, when the mountain was climbed by Polish climbers.<ref>Carter 1957, pp.240-241</ref>\n\nA 2006 article in Andes Magazine offered that Ojos del Salado may be higher than Aconcagua, although the argument was premised on older, less accurate altitude surveys. The results of these older surveys assigned Ojos del Salado an elevation of {{convert|7057|m|abbr=on}}, which would have made it nearly {{convert|100|m|abbr=on}} higher than Aconcagua. As early as 1955, an estimate was made that the elevation of Ojos del Salado was {{convert|7100|m|abbr=on}}, but that was \"simply [...] based on the altitude of the final camp, and the hours of ascent to the summit.\"<ref name=\"aaj_1956\">''American Alpine Journal'', 1956, p. 134; quoting the \"Boletin Informativo No. 16\" (June 1955) of the Argentine ''Associaci\u00f3n Tucumana de Andismo''.</ref> In 1956, the first Chilean expedition led by the retired [[lieutenant]] Ren\u00e9 Gajardo measured the height of Ojos del Salado as {{convert|7084|m|abbr=on}} with a pocket pressure [[altimeter]]. Apart from being an inexact method, the height shown by the altimeter was far too high as [[air pressure]] is generally lower in the afternoon, the time at which the team reached the summit.{{sfn|Lliboutry|1956}}\n\nAn expedition to the area in the 1990s claimed that nearby [[Monte Pissis]] was even higher than Ojos del Salado. Later measurements using more precise equipment showed that Ojos del Salado is about {{convert|100|m|abbr=on}} higher than Pissis. Furthermore, in 2007 a Chilean\u2013Argentine\u2013European expedition organized by Andes Magazine and Azimut 360 performed a survey on both Ojos del Salado and Monte Pissis using more accurate instruments. It found the former to be {{convert|6891|m|abbr=on}} and the latter {{convert|6793|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Phillipe\">{{cite web|url=http://andesinternacional.blogspot.com/2007/05/phillipe-reuter-el-ojos-del-salado-es.html|title=A la B\u00fasqueda del Techo de Am\u00e9rica|quote=Phillipe Reuter: \"El Ojos del Salado es 100 metros m\u00e1s alto que el Pissis\"|language=Spanish}}</ref> Although this fits within recent handheld [[GPS]] surveys, which have estimated the mountain to be between {{convert|6880|m|abbr=on}} and {{convert|6910|m|abbr=on}}, the vertical error margin of the expedition's equipment, {{convert|10|m|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"Phillipe\"/> leaves uncertainty as to the mountain's more precise altitude.\n\nA DGPS study from Phillipe Reuter in 2007, measured Ojos del Salado as 6,891.7 meters (SIRGAS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://andesinternacional.blogspot.com/2007/05/phillipe-reuter-el-ojos-del-salado-es.html|title=Phillipe Reuter: \"El Ojos del Salado es 100 metros m\u00e1s alto que el Pissis\"|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nOjos del Salado has two summits, one in Argentina and the other in Chile (the border between the two countries runs between the two summits). The difference in elevation of the two summits is less than {{convert|1|m|abbr=on}}\n\n==Motorized partial ascent==\n[[File:Rheinmetall MAN HX truck 1.jpg|left|thumb|The two [[RMMV HX range of tactical trucks|RMMV HX]] \u00a0]]\nOjos del Salado has been a popular mountain for attempts to attain the highest altitude aboard a land vehicle.\n\n[[File:Suzuki Samurai near the summit of Ojos del Salado.jpg|thumb|Suzuki Samurai in 2007|alt=]]\nThe current record altitude for a four-wheeled vehicle was set on April 21, 2007 by the Chilean duo of Gonzalo Bravo G. and Eduardo Canales Moya. Reaching an altitude of 6,688 meters (21,942&nbsp;ft.) with a modified [[Suzuki Jimny|Suzuki Samurai]], the duo beat the previous record of 6,646 m which had been set on March 13, 2007 by German Matthias Jeschke in a [[Jeep Wrangler]] Unlimited Rubicon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.streetdirectory.com/travel_guide/54035/car_focus/matthias_jeschke_set_new_high_altitude_world_record_aboard_.html|title=Matthias Jeschke Set New High Altitude World Record Aboard |publisher=streetdirectory.com|work=Editorials|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJeschke currently holds the high altitude record for trucks reaching a height of 6,675 meters (21,899&nbsp;ft) with a [[Mercedes-Benz Zetros]] truck on March 6, 2015. This is also a world record for a diesel-powered engine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://truckworldrecord.wordpress.com/author/extremeventsmj/|title=Truck World Record |publisher=Extreme Events|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 19, 2015 Chilean Gianfranco Bianchi reached an altitude of 6,472 m (21,233&nbsp;ft) with a Suzuki RMZ 450, setting the altitude record for a motorcycle.\n\nThe latest publicized record attempt commenced on November 6, 2017 and again involved Matthias Jeschke. With two [[RMMV HX range of tactical trucks|RMMV HX]] trucks Jeschke attempted to gain two world records, one for construction at altitude and the other by beating the current 6,688 m record.<ref>Rheinmetall MAN High Altitude Truck Expedition</ref> A refuge hut was built at 6,100 m (a record), but on December 19 it was announced the altitude record attempt had been called off at a height of 6,150 m for a combination of factors including an insurmountable rock barrier and adverse weather conditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rheinmetall.com/en/rheinmetall_ag/truck_expedition/news_1/index.php|title=Off-road expedition makes the world's tallest active volcano safer for climbers; attempt to set new world record temporarily thwarted |publisher=Rheinmetall|accessdate=December 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cerro El Muerto]]\n* [[Cerro Solo]]\n* [[Incapillo]]\n* [[Incahuasi]]\n* [[Laguna Verde (lake of Chile)|Laguna Verde]]\n* [[List of volcanoes in Argentina]]\n* [[List of volcanoes in Chile]]\n* [[Lists of volcanoes]]\n* [[Llullaillaco]]\n*[[Monte Pissis]]\n* [[Nevado Tres Cruces]]\n* [[Tipas]]\n* [[Volcanic Seven Summits]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite journal|last1=Baker|first1=P. E.|last2=Gonzalez-Ferran|first2=O.|last3=Rex|first3=D. C.|title=Geology and geochemistry of the Ojos del Salado volcanic region, Chile|journal=Journal of the Geological Society|date=1 February 1987|volume=144|issue=1|pages=85\u201396|doi=10.1144/gsjgs.144.1.0085|url=http://jgs.lyellcollection.org/content/144/1/85.short|language=en|issn=0016-7649}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Carter|first1=Adams|title=The American Alpine Club Expedition to the Ojos del Salado|journal=Geographical Review|date=1957|volume=47|issue=2|pages=240\u2013250|doi=10.2307/211595|jstor=211595}}\n* {{cite book|author=Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B|year=1996|via=[[ResearchGate]]|chapter-url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285978212|pages=539\u2013548|chapter=Geolog\u00eda de la regi\u00f3n de Ojos del Salado (Andes centrales, 27\u00b0S): Implicancias de la migraci\u00f3n hacia el este del frente volc\u00e1nico Cenozoico Superior|language=es|title=13\u00b0 Congreso Geol\u00f3gico Argentino}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|first=Ed|last=Darack|title=Wild Winds: Adventures in the Highest Andes|publisher=Cordee / DPP|year=2001|isbn=978-1884980817|language=English}} \n* {{cite book|first=Oscar|last=Gonzales-Ferran|title=Volcanes de Chile|location=Santiago, Chile|publisher=Instituto Geogr\u00e1fico Militar|year=1995|isbn=978-956-202-054-1|page=640|language=Spanish}} <small>(Also includes volcanoes of Argentina, Bolivia, and Peru)</small>\n* {{cite book | title=Volcanoes of the Central Andes\n  | last1=De Silva|first1=Shanaka L. | last2=Francis|first2=Peter\n  |publisher=Springer-Verlag | year=1991 | isbn=978-3-540-53706-9 | page=216}}\n* {{cite book|last=Biggar|first=John|title=The Andes: A Guide for Climbers|edition=3|publisher=Andes Publishing|location=Scotland|year=2005|url=http://www.andes.org.uk/andes-guidebooks.asp|isbn=978-0-9536087-2-0 |page=304}}\n* {{cite book|last=Lliboutry|first=Luis|authorlink=Luis Lliboutry|title=Nieves y Glaciares de Chile: Fundamentos de glaciolog\u00eda|year= 1956|language=Spanish |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ojos del Salado}}\n* [http://www.andeshandbook.org/montanismo/cerro/8/Ojos_del_Salado Complete description of Ojos del Salado in Andeshandbook]\n* [http://antwrp.gsfc.nasa.gov/apod/ap061202.html 1 December 2006 Star Trails at 19,000 Feet] - NASA Astronomy Picture of the Day\n* [http://www.andes.org.uk/andes-information-files/6000m-peaks.asp Andes information]\n*[http://www.andes-specialists.com/andean-mountains-5000/ Ojos del Salado Satellite Elevation Data]\n* [http://www.peakbagger.com/peak.aspx?pid=8569 Peak bagger]\n* [http://www.summitpost.org/show/mountain_link.pl/mountain_id/126 Summit post]\n* [http://www.peaklist.org/WWsurveys/SA/ojos.html Peak list]\n* [https://www.4dvt.com/ojos-del-salado-chile-argentina.html Virtual Aerial Video]\n\n{{Andean volcanoes}}\n{{Seven Second Summits}}\n{{Volcanic Seven Summits}}\n\n<!--Note that Category:Stratovolcanoes of Chile is a subcat of Category:Mountains of Chile -->\n\n[[Category:Stratovolcanoes of Chile]]\n[[Category:Stratovolcanoes of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Seven Second Summits]]\n[[Category:Volcanic Seven Summits]]\n[[Category:Active volcanoes]]\n[[Category:Andean Volcanic Belt]]\n[[Category:Volcanic crater lakes]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Atacama Region]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Atacama Region]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of Catamarca Province]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Catamarca Province]]\n[[Category:Atacama Desert]]\n[[Category:Argentina\u2013Chile border]]\n[[Category:International mountains of South America]]\n[[Category:Highest points of countries]]\n[[Category:Six-thousanders of the Andes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name            = Ojos del Salado\n| photo           = Ojos del Salado looming big on the horizon.jpg\n| photo_caption   = The volcano looming on the horizon.\n| elevation_m     = 6893\n| elevation_ref   = <ref name=\"peaklist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.peaklist.org/WWlists/ultras/andes1.html|title=Andes ultra-prominent peaks|publisher=Peaklist}}</ref>\n| prominence_m    = 3688\n| prominence_ref  = <ref name=\"peaklist\"/><br/><small>[[List of peaks by prominence|Ranked 44th]]</small>\n| listing         = [[Volcanic Seven Summits]]<br/>[[Seven Second Summits]]<br/>[[List of elevation extremes by country|Country high point]]<br/>[[Ultra-prominent peak|Ultra]]\n| location        = [[Argentina]]\u2013[[Chile]]\n| range           = [[Andes]]\n| map             = Chile\n| map_caption     = Location on the Argentina\u2013Chile border\n| label_position  = left\n| coordinates     = {{coord|27|06|35|S|68|32|29|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref = \n| topo            = Highest mountain: Highest Mountain in Chile\n| type            = [[stratovolcano]]\n| age             = \n| last_eruption   = 700 AD \u00b1 300 years<ref name=\"smithsonian\"/>\n| first_ascent    = February 26, 1937 by Jan Alfred Szczepa\u0144ski and Justyn Wojsznis\n| easiest_route   = [[Scrambling|Scramble]]\n}}\n[[File:Volcanic Landscapes, Central Andes labelled.jpg|thumb|350px|Volcanic Landscapes of the Central Andes. Shown are Nevado Ojos del Salado, [[Cerro El C\u00f3ndor]], and [[Peinado]], along the Argentina-Chile border. Astronaut photo from [[International Space Station]], 2010]]\n'''Nevado Ojos del Salado''' is an active [[stratovolcano]] in the [[Andes]] on the [[Argentina]]\u2013[[Chile]] border and the highest active [[volcano]] in the world at {{convert|6893|m|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Axel |last1=Borsdorf |first2=Christoph |last2=Stadel |title=The Andes: A Geographical Portrait |date=March 12, 2015 |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]] |isbn=978-3-319-03530-7 |page=7}}</ref> It is also the second highest mountain in both the [[Western Hemisphere]] and the [[Southern Hemisphere]] behind [[Aconcagua]] at approximately 7,000 meters (22,966 ft) and it is the highest in Chile. Nevado Ojos del Salado is translated to Snowy Salty Eyes describing it being very snowy in the winter and salty with many lakes. \n\nDue to its location near the [[Atacama Desert]], the mountain has very dry conditions, with snow usually only remaining on the peak during winter, though heavy storms can cover the surrounding area with a few feet of snow even in summer. Despite the generally dry conditions, there is a permanent [[Volcanic crater lake|crater lake]] about {{convert|100|m|abbr=on}} in diameter at an elevation of {{convert|6390|m|abbr=on}} on the eastern side of the mountain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andes.org.uk/peak-info-6000/ojos-del-salado-info.asp|title=Andes Website \u2013 Information about Ojos del Salado volcano, a high mountain in South America and the World's highest volcano<!-- Bot generated title -->}}</ref> This is most likely the [[Lake#Notable lakes on Earth|highest lake]] of any kind in the world.\n\nThe ascent of Ojos del Salado is mostly a hike except for the final section to the summit which is a difficult scramble that may require ropes. The first ascent was made in 1937 by [[Jan Alfred Szczepa\u0144ski]] and Justyn Wojsznis, members of a [[Poland|Polish]] expedition in the Andes.\n\nIts name, meaning roughly \"Eyes of the Salty One\" in [[Spanish language|Spanish]], comes from the enormous deposits of salt that, in the form of lagoons or \u201ceyes\u201d, appear in its [[glacier]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.los6000dechile.cl/cumbres_eng/21_ojosdelsalado.html|title=Los 6000 de Chile|publisher=Banco de Chile|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713082419/http://www.los6000dechile.cl/cumbres_eng/21_ojosdelsalado.html|archivedate=July 13, 2007}}</ref> An international highway between Chile and Argentina runs north of the mountain.<ref>Carter 1957, p.242</ref>\n\n==Geology and geomorphology==\n\n=== Regional ===\n\nOjos del Salado along with several other high volcanoes such as [[El Muerto]], [[El Solo]], [[Incahuasi|Nevado Incahuasi]] and [[Nevado Tres Cruces]] lies at the southern end of the [[Central Volcanic Zone]] of the Andes.<ref name=\"Mpodozis 1996, p.539\">Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B, 1996, p.539</ref>\n\nVolcanic activity in the region commenced 26 million years ago in the [[Cordillera Claudio Gay]], at the same time as the neighbouring [[Maricunga Belt]] volcanoes were active. Starting 18 million years ago, local [[subduction]] of the [[Nazca Plate]] beneath the [[South America Plate]] became increasingly shallower and this caused volcanism to shift from the Maricunga Belt to the Ojos del Salado region.<ref name=\"Mpodozis 1996, p.539\"/>\n\nThe [[Paleozoic]] basement crops out only northwest of Nevado Tres Cruces. Other geologic units in the region are [[Oligocene]] sedimentary units and volcanic rocks ranging from Oligocene age to less than 1.5 million years old.<ref>Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B, 1996, p.541</ref> The area is part of a tectonic boundary between a volcanically active region north of the boundary and a less volcanically active region south of the boundary, which is also characterized by geographical differences, e.g. the presence of transverse valleys.<ref>P. E. BAKER, O. GONZALEZ-FERRAN and D. C. REX, 1987 p.85</ref>\n\n=== Local ===\n\nOjos del Salado like other major neighbouring mountains is a complex of [[lava dome]]s and [[lava flow]]s, with the main summit surrounded by peripheral domes such as El Solo and El Fraile<ref>Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B, 1996, p.545</ref> and many other lateral centres.<ref>Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B, 1996, p.546</ref> [[Fumarole]]s are encountered at the summit of Ojos del Salado within a depression.<ref>P. E. BAKER, O. GONZALEZ-FERRAN and D. C. REX, 1987 p.90</ref> [[Potassium-argon dating]] has yielded ages of 1.2 \u00b1 0.3 million years ago and less than 1 million years ago from rocks north of Ojos del Salado.<ref>Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B, 1996, p.542</ref>\n\nThere are [[glacier]]s on the mountain, in the crater and in the form of [[penitente (snow formation)|penitente]]s<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://revistanortegrande.cl/n/14/inventario-de-glaciares-de-los-andes-chilenos-desde-los-18o-a-los-32o-de-latitud-sur/|title=Inventario de glaciares de los Andes chilenos desde los 18\u00ba a los 32\u00ba de latitud sur|date=March 8, 2014|work=Revista Geograf\u00eda Norte Grande|access-date=March 6, 2018|language=es-ES}}</ref> which reach heights of {{convert|8|-|5|m}}.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lliboitry|first1=Louis|title=The Origin of Penitents|journal=Journal of Glaciology|date=1954|volume=2|issue=15|page=334|doi=10.3189/S0022143000025181|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-glaciology/article/div-classtitlethe-origin-of-penitentsdiv/FACAAF8EF9A38B0F14AE85DC6805B8C7|language=en|issn=0022-1430}}</ref> Other reports indicate the absence of glaciers on Ojos del Salado. [[Permafrost]] exists on the mountain and its melting nourishes several lakes; one lake fed by a creek lies at {{convert|6500|m}} altitude.<ref name=\"Aszalos2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Aszal\u00f3s|first1=J\u00falia Margit|last2=Krett|first2=Gergely|last3=Anda|first3=D\u00f3ra|last4=M\u00e1rialigeti|first4=K\u00e1roly|last5=Nagy|first5=Bal\u00e1zs|last6=Borsodi|first6=Andrea K.|title=Diversity of extremophilic bacteria in the sediment of high-altitude lakes located in the mountain desert of Ojos del Salado volcano, Dry-Andes|journal=Extremophiles|date=September 1, 2016|volume=20|issue=5|pages=603\u2013620|doi=10.1007/s00792-016-0849-3|pmid=27315168|language=en|issn=1431-0651}}</ref>\n\nOjos del Salado is an active [[volcano]], but the question of whether it should be considered ''currently'' (or \"historically\") active is arguable. According to the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s [[Global Volcanism Program]],<ref name=\"smithsonian\">{{cite gvp|vnum=1505-13=|title=Ojos del Salado}}</ref> the most recent known eruption was about 1,300 years ago, with a large margin of uncertainty. However, there is also some evidence for a minor ash emission in 1993, which would definitely qualify the volcano as historically active. The presence of [[fumarole]]s high on the mountain and recent-looking [[lava]] flows, albeit of uncertain age, also argues in favor of a categorization as \"active.\"  By these definitions, Ojos del Salado is the highest historically active volcano on Earth. If the older date is accepted, the title of \"highest historically active volcano\" might reside instead with the somewhat lower [[Llullaillaco]] volcano, which certainly has erupted in historic times (most recently in 1877) and is considered active.\n\n===Composition===\nSalado's rock is predominantly [[potassium]]-rich [[dacite]] and [[rhyodacite]]. Its lavas are high in [[biotite]], [[hornblende]], [[plagioclase]], and opaques, with lower levels of [[augite]], quartz, and [[hypersthene]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://volcano.oregonstate.edu/oldroot/CVZ/ojossalado/index.html|title=Nevados Ojos del Salado|publisher=[[Oregon State University]]|work=Volcano World|year=2011|accessdate=July 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Elevation==\nThe elevation of Ojos del Salado has been the subject of debate. The mountain is hidden behind other peaks and thus its height was not appreciated in early research until 1937, when the mountain was climbed by Polish climbers.<ref>Carter 1957, pp.240-241</ref>\n\nA 2006 article in Andes Magazine offered that Ojos del Salado may be higher than Aconcagua, although the argument was premised on older, less accurate altitude surveys. The results of these older surveys assigned Ojos del Salado an elevation of {{convert|7057|m|abbr=on}}, which would have made it nearly {{convert|100|m|abbr=on}} higher than Aconcagua. As early as 1955, an estimate was made that the elevation of Ojos del Salado was {{convert|7100|m|abbr=on}}, but that was \"simply [...] based on the altitude of the final camp, and the hours of ascent to the summit.\"<ref name=\"aaj_1956\">''American Alpine Journal'', 1956, p. 134; quoting the \"Boletin Informativo No. 16\" (June 1955) of the Argentine ''Associaci\u00f3n Tucumana de Andismo''.</ref> In 1956, the first Chilean expedition led by the retired [[lieutenant]] Ren\u00e9 Gajardo measured the height of Ojos del Salado as {{convert|7084|m|abbr=on}} with a pocket pressure [[altimeter]]. Apart from being an inexact method, the height shown by the altimeter was far too high as [[air pressure]] is generally lower in the afternoon, the time at which the team reached the summit.{{sfn|Lliboutry|1956}}\n\nAn expedition to the area in the 1990s claimed that nearby [[Monte Pissis]] was even higher than Ojos del Salado. Later measurements using more precise equipment showed that Ojos del Salado is about {{convert|100|m|abbr=on}} higher than Pissis. Furthermore, in 2007 a Chilean\u2013Argentine\u2013European expedition organized by Andes Magazine and Azimut 360 performed a survey on both Ojos del Salado and Monte Pissis using more accurate instruments. It found the former to be {{convert|6891|m|abbr=on}} and the latter {{convert|6793|m|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Phillipe\">{{cite web|url=http://andesinternacional.blogspot.com/2007/05/phillipe-reuter-el-ojos-del-salado-es.html|title=A la B\u00fasqueda del Techo de Am\u00e9rica|quote=Phillipe Reuter: \"El Ojos del Salado es 100 metros m\u00e1s alto que el Pissis\"|language=Spanish}}</ref> Although this fits within recent handheld [[GPS]] surveys, which have estimated the mountain to be between {{convert|6880|m|abbr=on}} and {{convert|6910|m|abbr=on}}, the vertical error margin of the expedition's equipment, {{convert|10|m|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"Phillipe\"/> leaves uncertainty as to the mountain's more precise altitude.\n\nOjos del Salado has two summits, one in Argentina and the other in Chile (the border between the two countries runs between the two summits). The difference in elevation of the two summits is less than {{convert|1|m|abbr=on}}\n\n==Motorized partial ascent==\n[[File:Rheinmetall MAN HX truck 1.jpg|left|thumb|The two [[RMMV HX range of tactical trucks|RMMV HX]] \u00a0]]\nOjos del Salado has been a popular mountain for attempts to attain the highest altitude aboard a land vehicle.\n\n[[File:Suzuki Samurai near the summit of Ojos del Salado.jpg|thumb|Suzuki Samurai in 2007|alt=]]\nThe current record altitude for a four-wheeled vehicle was set on April 21, 2007 by the Chilean duo of Gonzalo Bravo G. and Eduardo Canales Moya. Reaching an altitude of 6,688 meters (21,942&nbsp;ft.) with a modified [[Suzuki Jimny|Suzuki Samurai]], the duo beat the previous record of 6,646 m which had been set on March 13, 2007 by German Matthias Jeschke in a [[Jeep Wrangler]] Unlimited Rubicon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.streetdirectory.com/travel_guide/54035/car_focus/matthias_jeschke_set_new_high_altitude_world_record_aboard_.html|title=Matthias Jeschke Set New High Altitude World Record Aboard |publisher=streetdirectory.com|work=Editorials|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJeschke currently holds the high altitude record for trucks reaching a height of 6,675 meters (21,899&nbsp;ft) with a [[Mercedes-Benz Zetros]] truck on March 6, 2015. This is also a world record for a diesel-powered engine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://truckworldrecord.wordpress.com/author/extremeventsmj/|title=Truck World Record |publisher=Extreme Events|accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 19, 2015 Chilean Gianfranco Bianchi reached an altitude of 6,472 m (21,233&nbsp;ft) with a Suzuki RMZ 450, setting the altitude record for a motorcycle.\n\nThe latest publicized record attempt commenced on November 6, 2017 and again involved Matthias Jeschke. With two [[RMMV HX range of tactical trucks|RMMV HX]] trucks Jeschke attempted to gain two world records, one for construction at altitude and the other by beating the current 6,688 m record.<ref>Rheinmetall MAN High Altitude Truck Expedition</ref> A refuge hut was built at 6,100 m (a record), but on December 19 it was announced the altitude record attempt had been called off at a height of 6,150 m for a combination of factors including an insurmountable rock barrier and adverse weather conditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rheinmetall.com/en/rheinmetall_ag/truck_expedition/news_1/index.php|title=Off-road expedition makes the world's tallest active volcano safer for climbers; attempt to set new world record temporarily thwarted |publisher=Rheinmetall|accessdate=December 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cerro El Muerto]]\n* [[Cerro Solo]]\n* [[Incapillo]]\n* [[Incahuasi]]\n* [[Laguna Verde (lake of Chile)|Laguna Verde]]\n* [[List of volcanoes in Argentina]]\n* [[List of volcanoes in Chile]]\n* [[Lists of volcanoes]]\n* [[Llullaillaco]]\n*[[Monte Pissis]]\n* [[Nevado Tres Cruces]]\n* [[Tipas]]\n* [[Volcanic Seven Summits]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite journal|last1=Baker|first1=P. E.|last2=Gonzalez-Ferran|first2=O.|last3=Rex|first3=D. C.|title=Geology and geochemistry of the Ojos del Salado volcanic region, Chile|journal=Journal of the Geological Society|date=1 February 1987|volume=144|issue=1|pages=85\u201396|doi=10.1144/gsjgs.144.1.0085|url=http://jgs.lyellcollection.org/content/144/1/85.short|language=en|issn=0016-7649}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Carter|first1=Adams|title=The American Alpine Club Expedition to the Ojos del Salado|journal=Geographical Review|date=1957|volume=47|issue=2|pages=240\u2013250|doi=10.2307/211595|jstor=211595}}\n* {{cite book|author=Mpodozis, C and Kay, Suzanne and Gardeweg, M and Coira, B|year=1996|via=[[ResearchGate]]|chapter-url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285978212|pages=539\u2013548|chapter=Geolog\u00eda de la regi\u00f3n de Ojos del Salado (Andes centrales, 27\u00b0S): Implicancias de la migraci\u00f3n hacia el este del frente volc\u00e1nico Cenozoico Superior|language=es|title=13\u00b0 Congreso Geol\u00f3gico Argentino}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|first=Ed|last=Darack|title=Wild Winds: Adventures in the Highest Andes|publisher=Cordee / DPP|year=2001|isbn=978-1884980817|language=English}} \n* {{cite boo