{"title_page": "John Mahama", "text_new": "{{short description|Former President of the Republic of Ghana}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = John Dramani Mahama\n|image         = John Dramani Mahama 2014 (cropped).jpg\n|office        = [[President of Ghana]]\n|vicepresident = [[Kwesi Amissah-Arthur]]\n|term_start    = 24 July 2012\n|term_end      = 7 January 2017\n|predecessor   = [[John Atta-Mills]]\n|successor     = [[Nana Akufo-Addo]]\n|office1       = Chair of the [[Economic Community of West African States]]\n|term_start1   = 28 March 2014\n|term_end1     = 19 May 2015\n|predecessor1  = [[Alassane Ouattara]]\n|successor1    = [[Macky Sall]]\n|office2       = [[Vice-President of Ghana|Vice President of Ghana]]\n|president2    = [[John Atta Mills]]\n|term_start2   = 7 January 2009\n|term_end2     = 24 July 2012\n|predecessor2  = [[Aliu Mahama]]\n|successor2    = [[Kwesi Amissah-Arthur]]\n|office3       = [[Minister for Communications (Ghana)|Minister of Communications]]\n|president3    = [[Jerry John Rawlings]]\n|term_start3   = November 1998\n|term_end3     = January 2001\n|predecessor3  = [[Ekwow Spio-Garbrah]]\n|successor3    = [[Felix Owusu-Adjapong]]\n|office4       = Member of Parliament<br />for [[Bole (Ghana parliament constituency)|Bole]]\n|term_start4   = 7 January 1997\n|term_end4     = 7 January 2009\n|predecessor4  = Mahama Jeduah\n|successor4    = [[Joseph Akati Saaka]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1958|11|29|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Damongo]], [[Ghana]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]]\n|spouse        = [[Lordina Mahama|Lordina Effah]]\n|children      = 5\n|relations     = {{unbulleted list|[[Emmanuel Adama Mahama]] (father)|[[Ibrahim Mahama (businessman)|Ibrahim Mahama]], Alfred Mahama,Peter Mahama, Malik Mahama (brothers)|[[Abiba Nnaba]] (mother)}}\n|education     = [[University of Ghana]]<br />Moscow Institute of Social Sciences\n|website       = {{url|johnmahama.org|Official website}}\n|signature     = John D Mahama signature.jpg\n}}\n'''John Dramani Mahama'''  {{pronunciation|En-us-John Dramani Mahama from Ghana pronunciation (Voice of America).ogg}} ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|h|\u0251\u02d0|m|\u0259}}; born 29 November 1958) is a [[Ghanaian people|Ghanaian politician]] who served as [[President of Ghana]] from 24 July 2012 to 7 January 2017. \n<!-- Edited out for NPOV concerns \nHe is believed to be the most corrupt and incompetent leader in the history of Ghana and the entire Africa. Also known as \"dead goat Mahama\"<ref>{{Cite or Government official 1 in the famous recent Airbus scandal \nweb|url=https://www.myjoyonline.com/politics/2015/March-11th/i-have-dead-goat-syndrome-mahama-tells-ghanaians.php|title=I have dead goat syndrome- Mahama tells Ghanaians - MyJoyOnline.com|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>, he never took any action against any act of corruption that were brought against his presidency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Mahama-is-corrupt-Spio-Garbrah-fires-680406|title=Mahama is corrupt \u2013 Spio-Garbrah fires|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref> He and his family are believed to be worth about $5.9 billion from looting public coffers and corruption<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Mahama-ate-drank-and-slept-with-corruption-so-cannot-be-incorruptible-NPP-Jabs-661755|title=Mahama ate, drank and slept with corruption; so cannot be incorruptible - NPP Jabs|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref> -->\n<!-- Don't edit to the 6th. Maintain consistency with all the previous presidents listed on Wikipedia -->He previously served as [[Vice President of Ghana]] from January 2009 to July 2012, and took office as President on 24 July 2012 following the death of his predecessor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/I-will-not-contest-in-2020-Mahama-498664 |title=I will not contest in 2020 - Mahama |website=www.ghanaweb.com |access-date=2017-01-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108001924/http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/I-will-not-contest-in-2020-Mahama-498664 |archivedate=8 January 2017 }}</ref> [[John Atta Mills]].<ref>\n[http://edition.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201207/90942.php MPs called to Parliament as CJ prepares to swear in John Mahama as president] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029194029/http://edition.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201207/90942.php |date=29 October 2013 }}    . ''edition.myjoyonline.com''.\n</ref> Mahama is a communication expert, historian, and writer. He was a Member of Parliament for Bole Bamboi from 1997 to 2009 and Minister of Communications from 1998 to 2001. He is a member of the NDC ([[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress).]]\n\nMahama is the first vice president to take over the presidency from the death of his predecessor, [[John Atta Mills|Prof. John Atta Mills]], and is the first head of state of Ghana to have been born after Ghana's independence. He was elected after [[2012 Ghanaian general election|December 2012 election]] to serve as full-time President.<ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-20661599 |work=BBC News |title=Ghana election: John Mahama declared winner |date=10 December 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121210061138/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-20661599 |archivedate=10 December 2012 }}</ref> He contested re-election for a second term in the [[2016 Ghanaian general election|2016 election]], but lost to the [[New Patriotic Party]] candidate [[Nana Akufo-Addo]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38270956 |title=Ghana election: Opposition leader Akufo-Addo declared winner |date=9 December 2016 |accessdate=16 December 2016 |via=www.bbc.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161212014907/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38270956 |archivedate=12 December 2016 |work=BBC News }}</ref> whom he defeated in 2012. This made him the first President in the history of [[History of Ghana|Ghana]] to not have won a second term.\n\nIn February 2019, Mahama was confirmed as the candidate of the opposition [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]] to contest in the 2020 elections, the incumbent president [[Nana Akufo-Addo]] who  unseated Mahama in a 2016 election, capitalizing on an economy that was slowing due to falling prices for gold, oil and cocoa exports.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ghana-politics-idUSKCN1QG246|title=Ghana's ex-President Mahama nominated to contest 2020 election|date=2019-02-27|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-01-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nA member of the [[Gonja people|Gonja]] ethnic group, Mahama hails from [[Bole, Ghana|Bole]] in the [[Northern Region (Ghana)|Northern Region]]. Mahama was born in [[Damongo]] in the [[Damango-Daboya (Ghana parliament constituency)|Damango-Daboya constituency]] of Northern region into a political tradition dating back to the country's [[First Republic of Ghana|First Republic]]. His father, [[Emmanuel Adama Mahama]], a wealthy rice [[farmer]] and teacher, was the first [[Member of Parliament]] for the [[West Gonja District|West Gonja]] constituency and the first Regional Commissioner of the [[Northern Region (Ghana)|Northern Region]] during the [[First Republic of Ghana|First Republic]] under Ghana's first president, [[Kwame Nkrumah]]. Mahama's father also served as a senior presidential advisor during Ghana's [[First Republic of Ghana|Third Republic]] under [Dr.[Hilla Limann who was overthrown in 1981 by Jerry Rawlings].\n\nMahama started his primary education at the Accra Newtown Experimental School (ANT1) and completed his O'levels education at [[Achimota School]] and his A'levels education at Ghana Secondary School ([[Tamale, Ghana|Tamale]], [[Northern Region (Ghana)|Northern region]]). He proceeded to the [[University of Ghana]], [[Legon]], receiving a bachelor's degree in history in 1981 and a postgraduate diploma in communication studies in 1986. As a student, he was a member of [[Commonwealth Hall Legon|Commonwealth Hall (Legon).]] He also studied at the Institute of Social Sciences in [[Moscow]] in the [[Soviet Union]], specializing in social psychology; he obtained a postgraduate degree in 1988.<ref name=bio2/>\n\n==Early career==\nAfter completing his undergraduate education, Mahama taught [[history]] at the [[secondary school]] level for a few years.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookbrowse.com/biographies/index.cfm/author_number/2199/john-mahama |title=John Mahama biography, plus links to book reviews and excerpts. |author=BookBrowse |work=BookBrowse.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906041129/https://www.bookbrowse.com/biographies/index.cfm/author_number/2199/john-mahama |archivedate=6 September 2015 }}</ref> Upon his return to Ghana after studying in [[Moscow]], he worked as the Information, Culture and Research Officer at the Embassy of Japan in [[Accra]] between 1991 and 1995.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnmahama.org/node/1 |title=Ghana |work=johnmahama.org |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231801/http://www.johnmahama.org/node/1 |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref> From there he moved to the anti-poverty [[non-governmental organisation]] (NGO) [[Plan International]]'s Ghana Country Office, where he worked as International Relations, Sponsorship Communications and Grants Manager between 1995 and 1996.<ref name=bio2/> In 1993, he participated in a professional training course for Overseas Public Relations Staff, organized by the Japanese [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] in [[Tokyo]]. He also participated in a management development course organized by [[Plan International]] (RESA) in [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]].<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceibs.edu/today/events/55601.shtml |title=Upcoming Events |work=ceibs.edu |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304123832/http://www.ceibs.edu/today/events/55601.shtml |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Political appointments==\n\n=== As Member of Parliament ===\nMahama was first elected to the Parliament of Ghana in the 1996 elections to represent the [[Bole District|Bole]]/Bamboi Constituency for a four-year term. In April 1997, Mahama was appointed Deputy Minister of Communications. He was promoted to the post of Minister of Communications in November 1998, serving in that post until January 2001, when the ruling [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]] (NDC) handed over power to the [[New Patriotic Party]]'s government.<ref name=bio/>\n\nIn 2000, Mahama was re-elected for another four-year term as the Member of Parliament for the Bole/Bamboi Constituency. He was again re-elected in 2004 for a third term. From 2001 to 2004, Mahama served as the Minority Parliamentary Spokesman for Communications. In 2002, he was appointed the Director of Communications for the NDC. That same year, he served as a member of the team of International Observers selected to monitor [[Zimbabwe]]'s Parliamentary Elections.<ref name=bio2>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanatoghana.com/Ghanahomepage/john-dramani-mahama-biography |title=John Dramani Mahama Biography |accessdate=24 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912122210/http://www.ghanatoghana.com/Ghanahomepage/john-dramani-mahama-biography |archivedate=12 September 2012 }}</ref>  As an [[Member of Parliament|MP]], he was a member of Standing Orders Committee as well as the Transport, Industry, Energy, Communications, Science and Technology Committee of Parliament.<ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/republic/president.php |title=Dr. John Dramani Mahama, President |work=ghanaweb.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602074327/http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/republic/president.php |archivedate=2 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== As Minister and Vice-President ===\nMahama served as the Deputy Minister of Communications between April 1997 and November 1998. During his tenure as Minister of Communications, Mahama also served as the Chairman of the National Communications Authority, in which capacity he played a key role in stabilising Ghana's telecommunications sector after it was deregulated in 1997. As a minister, he was a founding member of the Ghana AIDS Commission, a member of the implementation committee of the 2000 National Population Census and a deputy chairman of the Publicity Committee for the re-introduction of the [[Value Added Tax]] (VAT).\n\nContinuing to expand his interest and involvement in international affairs, in 2003 Mahama became a member of the Pan-African Parliament, serving as the Chairperson of the West African Caucus until 2011. He was also a member of European and Pan African Parliaments' Ad-hoc Committee on Cooperation.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> In 2005 he was, additionally, appointed the Minority Spokesman for Foreign Affairs. He is a member of the [[UNDP]] Advisory Committee on [[Conflict Resolution]] in Ghana.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nOn 7 January 2009, Mahama became the [[Vice-President of Ghana]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://people.peacefmonline.com/profiles/245/biography/ |title=John Mahama Biography |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728052946/http://people.peacefmonline.com/profiles/245/biography/ |archivedate=28 July 2012 }}</ref> He also served as the Chairman of the National Economic Management Team, the [[Armed Forces Council]] of Ghana, the Decentralisation and Implementation Committee and the Police Council of Ghana in this capacity.\n\n=== As President ===\nIn line with [[Constitution of Ghana|Ghana's constitution]], Mahama became President of Ghana on 24 July 2012 on the death of his predecessor, [[John Atta Mills]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-18972107 |title=Ghana's President John Atta Mills dies |publisher=BBC News |date=24 July 2012 |accessdate=24 July 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724184729/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-18972107 |archivedate=24 July 2012 }}</ref> In July 2012, he became the Ghana's first president to have served at all levels of political office (Ghanaian and Pan-African [[Member of Parliament|MP]], Deputy Minister, [[Minister (government)|Minister]], Vice-President and President). He said in parliament upon being sworn in:\n<blockquote>This is the saddest day in our nation's history. Tears have engulfed our nation and we are deeply saddened and distraught and I'm personally devastated, I've lost a father, I've lost a friend, I've lost a mentor and a senior comrade. Ghana is united in grief at this time for our departed president.<ref name=aljaz>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2012/07/20127259518486684.html |title=Ghana swears in Mahama as new president |work=Al Jazeera |date=25 July 2012 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726095044/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2012/07/20127259518486684.html |archivedate=26 July 2012 }}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Secretary Kerry Meets With Ghanaian President Mahama (9942939153).jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[President of Ghana]] John Mahama holds a [[Bilateralism|bilateral]] [[meeting]] with the [[United States Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]].]]\nAs a result of his elevation to the presidency, Mahama made political history by becoming the first [[List of heads of state of Ghana|Ghanaian head of state]] to have been born after Ghana's [[declaration of independence]] on 6 March 1957{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}https://www.johnmahama.org/biography/. The National Democratic Congress (NDC) held a Special National Delegates Congress on 30 August 2012 and endorsed President John Dramani Mahama as its 2012 presidential candidate. President Mahama, the sole candidate of the party, polled 2, 767 votes, representing 99.5% of total votes cast, to pick the slot for the party.<ref name=\"ndc endorses president mahama as 2012 presidential candidate\">.He is recorded as the most corrupt president to Ghana since independence with corruption scandals such as GYEEDA,SUBA,SADA,BUS BRANDING,WOYOME,AMERI POWER DEAL,KARPOWER DEAL,AKOMFEM FLYING TO BURKINA FASO,FORD EXPEDITION ,KUMASI AIRPORT RUNWAY SCANDAL several 100s of high profile corruptions deals under his regime.\nDuring his regime,he only relocates corrupt officials to the office of the president as punishment.He used inflated contracts as means to siphon billion of dollars of state funds into personal accounts.\n{{cite web |url=http://www.allghananews.com/politics/5110-ndc-endorses-president-mahama-as-2012-presidential-candidate |title=ALL GHANA NEWS - My bid for President is no melodrama-Akpaloo |author=GNA |work=allghananews.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112122741/http://www.allghananews.com/politics/5110-ndc-endorses-president-mahama-as-2012-presidential-candidate |archivedate=12 November 2014 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> Mahama has stated that his administration is deeply committed to continuing the [[Better Ghana Agenda]] started under President Mills.\n\nMahama won the [[2016 Ghanaian general election|December 2012 general election]] with 50.70% of the total valid votes cast and a 3% winning margin beating his nearest rival, [[Nana Akufo-Addo]] of the main opposition [[New Patriotic Party]], who polled a close 47.74%.  This was just barely enough to win the presidency without the need for a runoff.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> In addition, Mahama won the majority of valid votes cast in eight out of Ghana's ten administrative regions. Thirteen African Heads of State, one Prime Minister, two Vice-Presidents and 18 government delegations across the world attended his inaugural ceremony at the [[Black Star Square]] in [[Accra]] on 7 January 2013, when Mahama was sworn-in to begin his own four-year term.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201212/99293.php |title=11 Heads of States to attend Mahama's inauguration |author=Michael Ofori Amanfo Boateng |work=myjoyonline.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222102/http://edition.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201212/99293.php |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAfter his investiture, the opposition [[New Patriotic Party]] led by its 2012 presidential candidate [[Nana Akufo-Addo]], running mate Dr [[Mahamudu Bawumia]] and the party chairman [[Jacob Otanka Obetsebi-Lamptey]], challenged the election results, alleging irregularities, malpractices, omissions and violations. The petition was heard by nine justices of the [[Supreme Court of Ghana]]. After eight months of hearing, the Court on 29 August 2013 dismissed the petition by a majority opinion.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\nMahama is one of Africa's most-followed leaders on the social networking sites, [[Twitter]] and [[Facebook]].<ref>{{Citation\n |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21434229 \n |title=African Viewpoint: Which leaders are Twitter savvy? \n |publisher=BBC News \n |location=United Kingdom \n |date=13 February 2013 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130321204958/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21434229 \n |archivedate=21 March 2013 \n}}</ref> In May 2013, he stated that all of West Africa is under the threat of Islamist militancy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-22714242 |title=Militants threaten 'all West Africa' |newspaper=BBC News |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822235924/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-22714242 |archivedate=22 August 2016 |date=30 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2014, he was elected to preside over [[ECOWAS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/03/30/mahama-named-west-african-bloc-head |title=Mahama named West African bloc head |work=News |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511020255/http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/03/30/mahama-named-west-african-bloc-head |archivedate=11 May 2015 }}</ref> On 26 June 2014, he was elected Chairperson of the [[African Union]]\u2019s (AU's) High-Level African Trade Committee (HATC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2014/June-27th/prez-mahama-takes-over-from-idris-derby-as-aus-trade-committee-chair.php |title=Ghana News - Prez Mahama takes over from Idris Derby as AU's Trade Committee Chair |work=myjoyonline.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014105156/http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2014/June-27th/prez-mahama-takes-over-from-idris-derby-as-aus-trade-committee-chair.php |archivedate=14 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 January 2016 on the occasion of the World Economic Forum in Davos, Mahama became co-chair of the Sustainable Development Goals Advocates group which consists of 17 eminent persons assisting the UN Secretary-General in the campaign to achieve the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) that world leaders unanimously adopted in September 2015. With a mandate to support the Secretary-General in his efforts to generate momentum and commitment to achieve the SDGs by 2030, the SDG Advocates have been working to promote the universal sustainable development agenda, to raise awareness of the integrated nature of the SDGs, and to foster the engagement of new stakeholders in the implementation of these Goals.<ref>[https://www.un.org/sustainabledevelopment/sdgadvocates/#who Sustainable Development Goals Advocates] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331061653/http://www.un.org/sustainabledevelopment/sdgadvocates/ |date=31 March 2016 }}. Un.org. Retrieved on 2017-02-05.</ref>\n\nOn 9 December 2016, Mahama was defeated by the main opposition leader [[Nana Akufo-Addo]], to whom he conceded defeat earlier that day. Mahama polled 44.4% of the valid votes cast compared to Akufo-Addo's 53.5%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/12/ghana-akufo-addo-wins-presidential-election-161209172455364.html |title=Ghana: Akufo-Addo wins presidential election |accessdate=16 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161216012923/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/12/ghana-akufo-addo-wins-presidential-election-161209172455364.html |archivedate=16 December 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, he was part of part of the [[ECOWAS]] mediation team to resolve the post-election political impasse in [[The Gambia]] between the defeated incumbent, [[Yahya Jammeh]] and declared winner, [[Adama Barrow|Adam Barrow]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/lifestyle/2017/February-19th/happy-to-be-part-of-the-gambia-success-mahama.php |title=Happy to be part of The Gambia success - Mahama |last=Myjoyonline.com |date=2017-02-19 |access-date=2017-02-21 |language=en-US |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222052854/http://www.myjoyonline.com/lifestyle/2017/February-19th/happy-to-be-part-of-the-gambia-success-mahama.php |archivedate=22 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citifmonline.com/2017/02/19/our-success-in-the-gambia-signifies-ecowas-relevance-mahama/ |title=Our success in The Gambia signifies ECOWAS' relevance \u2013 Mahama |last=Ansah |first=Marian Efe |date=2017-02-19 |website=Ghana News |access-date=2017-02-21 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222055713/https://citifmonline.com/2017/02/19/our-success-in-the-gambia-signifies-ecowas-relevance-mahama/ |archivedate=22 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mobile.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Gambia-has-given-true-meaning-to-relevance-of-ECOWAS-Mahama-511592 |title=Gambia has given true meaning to relevance of ECOWAS - Mahama |website=mobile.ghanaweb.com |language=en |access-date=2017-02-21 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222053455/http://mobile.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Gambia-has-given-true-meaning-to-relevance-of-ECOWAS-Mahama-511592 |archivedate=22 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and interests==\n[[File:Lordina Dramani Mahama (cropped).jpg|thumb|150px|Ghanaian [[First Lady]] Lordina Mahama on 3 June 2014.]]\nMahama is married to [[Lordina Mahama]] (n\u00e9e Effah, 6 March 1963). Mahama has five children named Shafik, Shahid, Sharaf, Jesse and Farida. He is a [[Christians|Christian]], born and raised a [[Presbyterian]] but is now a member of the [[Assemblies of God]], Ghana by marriage.<ref name=bio/>  His family is multi-faith, consisting of Christians and [[Muslim]]s.<ref name=\"Sworn in as new\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20131002102354/http://www.gbcghana.com/index.php?id=1.977333 John Dramani Mahama Sworn-in As New President of Ghana, Calls For Unity Among Ghanaians], at the [[Ghana Broadcasting Corporation]]; published July 24, 2012; archived at [[archive.org]] October 2, 2013</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://gbcghana.com/index.php?launch=candidates_profile |title=Profile of Presidential Candidates\n |publisher=Ghana Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=16 December 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202203917/http://gbcghana.com/index.php?launch=candidates_profile |archivedate=2 February 2014 }}</ref>  Being a staunch campaigner for sustainability, he has a keen interest in environmental affairs, particularly the problem of [[single-use]] [[plastic pollution|plastic waste]] pollution in Africa, which he committed himself to addressing during his tenure as Vice President.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gbcghana.com/index.php/id=1.346245 |title=Govt committed to eliminating plastic waste-Veep |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002103046/http://www.gbcghana.com/index.php/id%3D1.346245 |archivedate=2 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOver the course of his career, Mahama has written for several newspapers and other publications both locally and internationally. As a [[Member of Parliament|Parliamentarian]], Mahama wrote ''Mahama's Hammer'', a semi-regular column in a Ghanaian newspaper. His essays have also been published in the ''[[Daily Graphic (Ghana)|Daily Graphic]]'', ''[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]'', ''[[Huffington Post]]'', the ''[[Louisville Courier-Journal]]'', the ''[[New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]''.<ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebony.com/news-views/bring-back-our-girls-african-heads-of-state-send-support-to-nigeria-304#.axzz31cRnVxcy |title=BRING BACK OUR GIRLS: African Heads of State Send Support to Nigeria |work=EBONY |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906093749/http://www.ebony.com/news-views/bring-back-our-girls-african-heads-of-state-send-support-to-nigeria-304 |archivedate=6 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebony.com/news-views/slaughtered-boys-missing-girls-who-stands-up-for-african-children#.U2ttyqKs9sX |title=Slaughtered Boys, Missing Girls: Who Stands Up for African Children? |work=EBONY |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906061603/http://www.ebony.com/news-views/slaughtered-boys-missing-girls-who-stands-up-for-african-children |archivedate=6 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://graphic.com.gh/features/opinion/22123-what-you-don-t-know.html |title=President Mahama writes: What you don't know |work=graphic.com.gh |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233504/http://www.graphic.com.gh/features/opinion/22123-what-you-don-t-know.html |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://nytimes.com/2013/12/06/opinion/mahama-mandela-taught-a-continent-to-forgive.html |work=The New York Times |title=Mandela Taught a Continent to Forgive |date=5 December 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209072934/http://www.nytimes.com//2013/12/06/opinion/mahama-mandela-taught-a-continent-to-forgive.html |archivedate=9 December 2013 }}</ref> Additionally, he was a featured speaker at the [[TEDx]] [[Great Pacific Garbage Patch]] [[Academic conference|Conference]] in [[Santa Monica]].<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Mahama is also a devotee of [[Afrobeat|Afrobeat music]], especially that of [[Fela Kuti]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/321487/ghanas-mahama-writer-music-fan-and-president-elect |title=Ghana's Mahama: writer, music fan and president-elect - Inquirer News |author=Agence France-Presse |work=inquirer.net |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304023600/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/321487/ghanas-mahama-writer-music-fan-and-president-elect |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref>  Apart from his hobby of reading, Mahama also has a passionate interest in innovation particularly the use of [[technology]] in agriculture being a farmer himself. In particular, he is interested in finding the most effective ways to improve agricultural productivity and works to encourage more young people to see farming as a viable business and not a subsistence activity. This has translated into his passion to see the Savanna Accelerated Development Authority (SADA) create new opportunities for people living in the Savanna areas of the country, which includes the three Northern Regions, and the [[Volta Region|Volta]] Region. Even on official assignments outside of country, Mahama likes to take advantage of opportunities to visit agricultural establishments and update himself on current trends and developments. He also takes keen interest in the opportunities for simplifying and making tasks easier with the use of [[information and communications technology]], and considers the [[Information and communication technologies|ICT]] industry one of the sectors that can play a significant role in economic transformation and job creation.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> He's an avid fan of motor biking and owns about 5 of them.\n\n===Books===\nMahama's first book, a memoir called [[''My First Coup d'\u00c9tat: Memories from the Lost Decades of Africa'']], was published by [[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]] on 3 July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.modernghana.com/news/434142/1/a-vote-for-john-mahama-is-an-endorsement-of-corrup.html |title=A Vote For John Mahama Is An Endorsement Of Corruption\u2014NPP Germany|accessdate=2013-01-31 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206041658/http://www.modernghana.com/news/434142/1/a-vote-for-john-mahama-is-an-endorsement-of-corrup.html |archivedate=6 February 2013 }}. ''[[Amazon.com]].''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theroot.com/views/ghana-s-new-leader-talks-africa-s-future |title=My First Coup D'Etat: Memoir Sheds Light on the Lost Decades |author=Akoto Ofori-Atta |date=24 July 2012 |work=The Root |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022204651/http://www.theroot.com/views/ghana-s-new-leader-talks-africa-s-future |archivedate=22 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/07/17/156506719/african-politics-and-afros-in-my-first-coup-detat |title=African Politics, And Afros, In 'My First Coup D'Etat' |date=17 July 2012 |work=NPR.org |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618172042/http://www.npr.org/2012/07/17/156506719/african-politics-and-afros-in-my-first-coup-detat |archivedate=18 June 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-10-12-book-review-my-first-coup-dtat-by-ghanas-accidental-president |title=Book review: My First Coup d'Etat, by Ghana's accidental president |work=dailymaverick.co.za |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618151333/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-10-12-book-review-my-first-coup-dtat-by-ghanas-accidental-president |archivedate=18 June 2015 }}</ref> The most promising son of an [[affluent]] government minister, he spends his childhood shuttling in his father's [[chauffeur]]-driven cars, from his elite boarding school [[Achimota School]] in Accra to his many [[home]]s. He recalls in its first chapter the day in 1966 when he learned of the ousting of Ghana's founding president, [[Kwame Nkrumah]], in a military coup: \"When I look back on my life it's clear to me that this moment marked the awakening of my consciousness. It changed my life and influenced all the moments that followed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starafrica.com/en/news/detail-news/view/mahama-writer-historian-and-ghanas-ne-244519.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130203030428/http://www.starafrica.com/en/news/detail-news/view/mahama-writer-historian-and-ghanas-ne-244519.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 February 2013 |title=Mahama: writer, historian and Ghana's new president \u00bb politics \u00bb News - StarAfrica.com - News \u2013 StarAfrica.com |work=Starafrica |accessdate=5 June 2015 }}</ref>{{clear}}\n\n===Corruption allegations===\nIt was revealed in 2016 that Mahama accepted a [[Ford Expedition]] from a construction firm bidding for a lucrative government contract in 2012, while he was serving as Vice President. The Burkinabe contractor who had previously constructed a wall at the Ghanaian Embassy in Ouagadougou was at the time looking to get a road-building contract in Ghana's Volta region; this contractor later secured the contract but the vehicle left by the ex president for Government use.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://citifmonline.com/2016/09/29/full-text-chrajs-report-on-mahamas-ford-gift-saga/|title=Full Text: CHRAJ's report on Mahama's Ford gift saga - Ghana News|date=2016-09-29|work=Ghana News|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918064321/http://citifmonline.com/2016/09/29/full-text-chrajs-report-on-mahamas-ford-gift-saga/|archivedate=18 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|title=Election 2016: Seven scandals that rocked the NDC under John Mahama|last=Staff|first=Pulse|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104164708/http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|archivedate=4 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|title=Election 2016: Seven scandals that rocked the NDC under John Mahama|last=Staff|first=Pulse|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104164708/http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|archivedate=4 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Under Mahama's presidency in 2014, massive corruption was discovered at Ghana's Savannah Accelerated Development Authority (SADA). The authority had misappropriated millions of dollars allocated to it. SADA paid GH\u20b532,498,000 to ACICL, a business owned by Ghana's Roland Agambire, Mahama's close confidante, to plant five million trees in the savannah zone, but could only account for about 700,000 trees. It was also discovered that SADA spent GH\u00a215 million on guinea fowl, but could only account for a few of the birds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/opinion/2014/April-15th/manassehs-folder-the-sad-sada-story-of-northern-ghanas-elite.php|title=Manasseh's Folder: The sad SADA story of northern Ghana's elite - MyJoyOnline.com|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2017-12-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017193749/http://www.myjoyonline.com/opinion/2014/April-15th/manassehs-folder-the-sad-sada-story-of-northern-ghanas-elite.php|archivedate=17 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|title=Election 2016: Seven scandals that rocked the NDC under John Mahama|last=Staff|first=Pulse|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104164708/http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|archivedate=4 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2015 it was again discovered that the contract for the rebranding of 116 Metro Mass Transit (MMT) buses at a cost of Gh\u20b53,600,000 was sole sourced and awarded to a company named \u201c''Smarttys,''\u201d owned by a member of the ruling NDC activist Selassie Ibrahim. It was revealed that the rebranding of the buses cost the government Gh\u20b53,600,000 which at the time was more than the cost of the 116 buses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|title=Election 2016: Seven scandals that rocked the NDC under John Mahama|last=Staff|first=Pulse|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104164708/http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|archivedate=4 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Honours and awards===\n[[File:John Dramani Mahama UNDP 2010.jpg|thumb|right|195px|John Dramani Mahama at the UNDP in 2010]]\nMahama received an [[honorary doctorate]] in the field of [[Public Administration]], from the [[Ekiti State]] University of [[Nigeria]], formerly affiliated to the [[Obafemi Awolowo]] University in \"recognition of his politico-socio economic development of Ghana and Africa at various stages of his political career.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gbcghana.com/index.php?launch=gallery&id=1.843195 |title=KITNES Page Error |accessdate=16 December 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220180128/http://www.gbcghana.com/index.php?launch=gallery&id=1.843195 |archivedate=20 December 2016 }}</ref> Later the same university passed a resolution to name its [[Faculty (division)|Faculty]] of [[Management Science]] after him.<ref>[http://www.myradiogoldlive.com/index.php/general-news/3400-nigerian-university-to-name-faculty-after-president-mahama Nigerian University to Name Faculty after President Mahama<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317045345/http://www.myradiogoldlive.com/index.php/general-news/3400-nigerian-university-to-name-faculty-after-president-mahama |date=17 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Cuba]]n government, recognising Mahama's relentless advocacy for the Cuban cause, namely for the lifting of the 50-year economic embargo on the communist country and for the freedom of the detained Cuban five by the United States government, conferred on him the Friendship Medal.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://iamaghanaian.com/index.php?do=/news/vice-president-john-mahama-honoured/ |title=Vice President John Mahama Honoured |author=phpFox |work=iamaghanaian.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317032332/http://iamaghanaian.com/index.php?do=%2Fnews%2Fvice-president-john-mahama-honoured%2F |archivedate=17 March 2014 }}</ref> {{citation needed|date=September 2017}}The General Council of [[Assemblies of God]], Ghana honoured Mahama with its Daniel Award.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130124123411/http://www.gbcghana.com/new/index.php?id=1.749979 GBC News, Vice President John Mahama honoured for exceptional leadership qualities<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The Graduate School of Governance and Leadership also awarded him the African Servant Leadership Award while the Institute of Public Relations recognized Mahama with a prize for his leadership acumen and technocratic flair.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> In 2013, the Forum for Agricultural Research in Africa (FARA) conferred on Mahama the Africa Award for Excellence in Food Security and Poverty Reduction.<ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.tv3network.com/Business/veep-calls-for-more-support-for-the-agric-sector.html |title=Veep calls for more support for the agric sector &#124; Business<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=14 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814015438/http://tv3network.com/Business/veep-calls-for-more-support-for-the-agric-sector.html |archive-date=14 August 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }} \n</ref> In March 2016, [[University of Aberdeen]] held a special convocation to confer an honorary degree of Doctors of Laws (LLD) on President John Mahama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2016/March-17th/mahama-gets-honorary-law-degree-from-aberdeen-university.php |title=Mahama gets honorary law degree from Aberdeen University - MyJoyOnline |last=Myjoyonline.com |accessdate=16 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525045211/http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2016/March-17th/mahama-gets-honorary-law-degree-from-aberdeen-university.php |archivedate=25 May 2016 }}</ref>\n\nMahama has also attended numerous conferences and won many fellowships, including a study as a [[visiting scholar]] at [[The Johns Hopkins University]], [[Baltimore]], United States. He is also a [[Bill Gates]] Fellow.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> He was awarded the Great Cross of the National Order of [[Benin]], the highest award in Benin, by President [[Yayi Boni]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghana.gov.gh/index.php/news-slider/2958-president-mahama-receives-national-order-of-benin |title=GHANA HOSTS INTERNATIONAL SYMPOSIUM ON THE ROLE OF REGULATION IN ICT DEVELOPMENT - Government of Ghana |first=Sule |last=Jotie |accessdate=16 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805143616/http://www.ghana.gov.gh/index.php/news-slider/2958-president-mahama-receives-national-order-of-benin |archivedate=5 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Mahama received the 2016 African Political Leader of the Year Award from the African Leadership Magazine in [[South Africa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citifmonline.com/2017/02/23/mahama-to-deliver-keynote-speech-at-african-leadership-magazine-awards/ |title=Mahama to deliver keynote speech at African Leadership Magazine awards |last=Adogla-Bessa |first=Delali |date=2017-02-23 |website=Ghana News |access-date=2017-02-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223084229/http://citifmonline.com/2017/02/23/mahama-to-deliver-keynote-speech-at-african-leadership-magazine-awards/ |archivedate=23 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pulse.com.gh/politics/congratulations-mahama-named-2016-best-african-political-leader-id6268121.html |title=Congratulations: Mahama named 2016 best African Political leader |last=Tornyi |first=Emmanuel |access-date=2017-02-23 |language=en-US |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224055607/http://pulse.com.gh/politics/congratulations-mahama-named-2016-best-african-political-leader-id6268121.html |archivedate=24 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://starrfmonline.com/?p=13321 |title=Mahama wins African Political Leader of the Year Award |date=2017-02-23 |newspaper=Starr Fm |access-date=2017-02-23 |language=en-US |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223065433/http://starrfmonline.com/?p=13321 |archivedate=23 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://medafricatimes.com/12073-ex-ghana-president-mahama-wins-africa-leadership-award.html |title=Ex-Ghana president Mahama wins Africa leadership award {{!}} Medafrica Times |website=medafricatimes.com |language=en-US |access-date=2017-02-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301180829/http://medafricatimes.com/12073-ex-ghana-president-mahama-wins-africa-leadership-award.html |archivedate=1 March 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/John-Mahama-s-keynote-address-at-2016-African-Leadership-Magazine-Person-of-the-Year-Awards-513166 |title=John Mahama's keynote address at 2016 African Leadership Magazine Person of the Year Awards |website=www.ghanaweb.com |access-date=2017-02-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301181700/http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/John-Mahama-s-keynote-address-at-2016-African-Leadership-Magazine-Person-of-the-Year-Awards-513166 |archivedate=1 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.johnmahama.org/}}\n* {{C-SPAN|John Mahama}}\n* {{commons-inline|Category:John Dramani Mahama|John Dramani Mahama}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gh}}\n{{s-bef|before=Mahama Jeduah}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Bole (Ghana parliament constituency)|Bole]]|years=1997\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=Joseph Akati Saaka}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ekwow Spio-Garbrah]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Communications (Ghana)|Minister for Communications]]|years=1998\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Felix Owusu-Adjapong]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Aliu Mahama]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Vice-President of Ghana|Vice President of Ghana]]|years=2009\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kwesi Amissah-Arthur]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Atta Mills]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Ghana]]|years=2012\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nana Akufo-Addo]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Muhammad Mumuni]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]] nominee for [[Vice President of Ghana]]|years=[[2008 Ghanaian general election|2008]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kwesi Amissah-Arthur]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Atta Mills]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]] nominee for [[List of heads of state of Ghana|President of Ghana]]|years=[[2012 Ghanaian general election|2012]],}}[[2016 Ghanaian general election|2016]]\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alassane Ouattara]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Economic Community of West African States]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Macky Sall]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Heads of State of Ghana}}\n{{GhanaVPs}}\n{{Ghana topics}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Africa|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahama, John}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century historians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Achimota School]]\n[[Category:Communication ministers of Ghana]]\n[[Category:Former Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian civil servants]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian commanders in chief]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian MPs 2005\u20132009]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian Pentecostals]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pan-African Parliament from Ghana]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Congress (Ghana) politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Northern Region (Ghana)]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Ghana]]\n[[Category:University of Ghana alumni]]\n[[Category:Vice-Presidents of Ghana]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Former President of the Republic of Ghana}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = John Dramani Mahama\n|image         = John Dramani Mahama 2014 (cropped).jpg\n|office        = [[President of Ghana]]\n|vicepresident = [[Kwesi Amissah-Arthur]]\n|term_start    = 24 July 2012\n|term_end      = 7 January 2017\n|predecessor   = [[John Atta-Mills]]\n|successor     = [[Nana Akufo-Addo]]\n|office1       = Chair of the [[Economic Community of West African States]]\n|term_start1   = 28 March 2014\n|term_end1     = 19 May 2015\n|predecessor1  = [[Alassane Ouattara]]\n|successor1    = [[Macky Sall]]\n|office2       = [[Vice-President of Ghana|Vice President of Ghana]]\n|president2    = [[John Atta Mills]]\n|term_start2   = 7 January 2009\n|term_end2     = 24 July 2012\n|predecessor2  = [[Aliu Mahama]]\n|successor2    = [[Kwesi Amissah-Arthur]]\n|office3       = [[Minister for Communications (Ghana)|Minister of Communications]]\n|president3    = [[Jerry John Rawlings]]\n|term_start3   = November 1998\n|term_end3     = January 2001\n|predecessor3  = [[Ekwow Spio-Garbrah]]\n|successor3    = [[Felix Owusu-Adjapong]]\n|office4       = Member of Parliament<br />for [[Bole (Ghana parliament constituency)|Bole]]\n|term_start4   = 7 January 1997\n|term_end4     = 7 January 2009\n|predecessor4  = Mahama Jeduah\n|successor4    = [[Joseph Akati Saaka]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1958|11|29|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Damongo]], [[Ghana]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]]\n|spouse        = [[Lordina Mahama|Lordina Effah]]\n|children      = 5\n|relations     = {{unbulleted list|[[Emmanuel Adama Mahama]] (father)|[[Ibrahim Mahama (businessman)|Ibrahim Mahama]], Alfred Mahama,Peter Mahama, Malik Mahama (brothers)|[[Abiba Nnaba]] (mother)}}\n|education     = [[University of Ghana]]<br />Moscow Institute of Social Sciences\n|website       = {{url|johnmahama.org|Official website}}\n|signature     = John D Mahama signature.jpg\n}}\n'''John Dramani Mahama'''  {{pronunciation|En-us-John Dramani Mahama from Ghana pronunciation (Voice of America).ogg}} ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|h|\u0251\u02d0|m|\u0259}}; born 29 November 1958) is a [[Ghanaian people|Ghanaian politician]] who served as [[President of Ghana]] from 24 July 2012 to 7 January 2017. \n<!-- Edited out for NPOV concerns \nHe is believed to be the most corrupt and incompetent leader in the history of Ghana and the entire Africa. Also known as \"dead goat Mahama\"<ref>{{Cite or Government official 1 in the famous recent Airbus scandal \nweb|url=https://www.myjoyonline.com/politics/2015/March-11th/i-have-dead-goat-syndrome-mahama-tells-ghanaians.php|title=I have dead goat syndrome- Mahama tells Ghanaians - MyJoyOnline.com|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>, he never took any action against any act of corruption that were brought against his presidency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Mahama-is-corrupt-Spio-Garbrah-fires-680406|title=Mahama is corrupt \u2013 Spio-Garbrah fires|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref> He and his family are believed to be worth about $5.9 billion from looting public coffers and corruption<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Mahama-ate-drank-and-slept-with-corruption-so-cannot-be-incorruptible-NPP-Jabs-661755|title=Mahama ate, drank and slept with corruption; so cannot be incorruptible - NPP Jabs|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref> -->\n<!-- Don't edit to the 6th. Maintain consistency with all the previous presidents listed on Wikipedia -->He previously served as [[Vice President of Ghana]] from January 2009 to July 2012, and took office as President on 24 July 2012 following the death of his predecessor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/I-will-not-contest-in-2020-Mahama-498664 |title=I will not contest in 2020 - Mahama |website=www.ghanaweb.com |access-date=2017-01-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108001924/http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/I-will-not-contest-in-2020-Mahama-498664 |archivedate=8 January 2017 }}</ref> [[John Atta Mills]].<ref>\n[http://edition.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201207/90942.php MPs called to Parliament as CJ prepares to swear in John Mahama as president] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029194029/http://edition.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201207/90942.php |date=29 October 2013 }}    . ''edition.myjoyonline.com''.\n</ref> Mahama is a communication expert, historian, and writer. He was a Member of Parliament for Bole Bamboi from 1997 to 2009 and Minister of Communications from 1998 to 2001. He is a member of the NDC ([[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress).]]\n\nMahama is the first vice president to take over the presidency from the death of his predecessor, [[John Atta Mills|Prof. John Atta Mills]], and is the first head of state of Ghana to have been born after Ghana's independence. He was elected after [[2012 Ghanaian general election|December 2012 election]] to serve as full time President.<ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-20661599 |work=BBC News |title=Ghana election: John Mahama declared winner |date=10 December 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121210061138/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-20661599 |archivedate=10 December 2012 }}</ref> He contested re-election for a second term in the [[2016 Ghanaian general election|2016 election]], but lost to the [[New Patriotic Party]] candidate [[Nana Akufo-Addo]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38270956 |title=Ghana election: Opposition leader Akufo-Addo declared winner |date=9 December 2016 |accessdate=16 December 2016 |via=www.bbc.com |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161212014907/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38270956 |archivedate=12 December 2016 |work=BBC News }}</ref> whom he defeated in 2012. This made him the first President in the history of [[History of Ghana|Ghana]] to not have won a second term.\n\nIn February 2019, Mahama was confirmed as the candidate of the opposition [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]] to contest in the 2020 elections, the incumbent president [[Nana Akufo-Addo]] who  unseated Mahama in a 2016 election, capitalizing on an economy that was slowing due to falling prices for gold, oil and cocoa exports.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ghana-politics-idUSKCN1QG246|title=Ghana's ex-President Mahama nominated to contest 2020 election|date=2019-02-27|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-01-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nA member of the [[Gonja people|Gonja]] ethnic group, Mahama hails from [[Bole, Ghana|Bole]] in the [[Northern Region (Ghana)|Northern Region]]. Mahama was born in [[Damongo]] in the [[Damango-Daboya (Ghana parliament constituency)|Damango-Daboya constituency]] of Northern region into a political tradition dating back to the country's [[First Republic of Ghana|First Republic]]. His father, [[Emmanuel Adama Mahama]], a wealthy rice [[farmer]] and teacher, was the first [[Member of Parliament]] for the [[West Gonja District|West Gonja]] constituency and the first Regional Commissioner of the [[Northern Region (Ghana)|Northern Region]] during the [[First Republic of Ghana|First Republic]] under Ghana's first president, [[Kwame Nkrumah]]. Mahama's father also served as a senior presidential advisor during Ghana's [[First Republic of Ghana|Third Republic]] under [Dr.[Hilla Limann who was overthrown in 1981 by Jerry Rawlings].\n\nMahama started his primary education at the Accra Newtown Experimental School (ANT1) and completed his O'levels education at [[Achimota School]] and his A'levels education at Ghana Secondary School ([[Tamale, Ghana|Tamale]], [[Northern Region (Ghana)|Northern region]]). He proceeded to the [[University of Ghana]], [[Legon]], receiving a bachelor's degree in history in 1981 and a postgraduate diploma in communication studies in 1986. As a student, he was a member of [[Commonwealth Hall Legon|Commonwealth Hall (Legon).]] He also studied at the Institute of Social Sciences in [[Moscow]] in the [[Soviet Union]], specializing in social psychology; he obtained a postgraduate degree in 1988.<ref name=bio2/>\n\n==Early career==\nAfter completing his undergraduate education, Mahama taught [[history]] at the [[secondary school]] level for a few years.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookbrowse.com/biographies/index.cfm/author_number/2199/john-mahama |title=John Mahama biography, plus links to book reviews and excerpts. |author=BookBrowse |work=BookBrowse.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906041129/https://www.bookbrowse.com/biographies/index.cfm/author_number/2199/john-mahama |archivedate=6 September 2015 }}</ref> Upon his return to Ghana after studying in [[Moscow]], he worked as the Information, Culture and Research Officer at the Embassy of Japan in [[Accra]] between 1991 and 1995.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://www.johnmahama.org/node/1 |title=Ghana |work=johnmahama.org |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231801/http://www.johnmahama.org/node/1 |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref> From there he moved to the anti-poverty [[non-governmental organisation]] (NGO) [[Plan International]]'s Ghana Country Office, where he worked as International Relations, Sponsorship Communications and Grants Manager between 1995 and 1996.<ref name=bio2/> In 1993, he participated in a professional training course for Overseas Public Relations Staff, organized by the Japanese [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] in [[Tokyo]]. He also participated in a management development course organized by [[Plan International]] (RESA) in [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]].<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceibs.edu/today/events/55601.shtml |title=Upcoming Events |work=ceibs.edu |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304123832/http://www.ceibs.edu/today/events/55601.shtml |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Political appointments==\n\n=== As Member of Parliament ===\nMahama was first elected to the Parliament of Ghana in the 1996 elections to represent the [[Bole District|Bole]]/Bamboi Constituency for a four-year term. In April 1997, Mahama was appointed Deputy Minister of Communications. He was promoted to the post of Minister of Communications in November 1998, serving in that post until January 2001, when the ruling [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress]] (NDC) handed over power to the [[New Patriotic Party]]'s government.<ref name=bio/>\n\nIn 2000, Mahama was re-elected for another four-year term as the Member of Parliament for the Bole/Bamboi Constituency. He was again re-elected in 2004 for a third term. From 2001 to 2004, Mahama served as the Minority Parliamentary Spokesman for Communications. In 2002, he was appointed the Director of Communications for the NDC. That same year, he served as a member of the team of International Observers selected to monitor [[Zimbabwe]]'s Parliamentary Elections.<ref name=bio2>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanatoghana.com/Ghanahomepage/john-dramani-mahama-biography |title=John Dramani Mahama Biography |accessdate=24 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912122210/http://www.ghanatoghana.com/Ghanahomepage/john-dramani-mahama-biography |archivedate=12 September 2012 }}</ref>  As an [[Member of Parliament|MP]], he was a member of Standing Orders Committee as well as the Transport, Industry, Energy, Communications, Science and Technology Committee of Parliament.<ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/republic/president.php |title=Dr. John Dramani Mahama, President |work=ghanaweb.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602074327/http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/republic/president.php |archivedate=2 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== As Minister and Vice-President ===\nMahama served as the Deputy Minister of Communications between April 1997 and November 1998. During his tenure as Minister of Communications, Mahama also served as the Chairman of the National Communications Authority, in which capacity he played a key role in stabilising Ghana's telecommunications sector after it was deregulated in 1997. As a minister, he was a founding member of the Ghana AIDS Commission, a member of the implementation committee of the 2000 National Population Census and a deputy chairman of the Publicity Committee for the re-introduction of the [[Value Added Tax]] (VAT).\n\nContinuing to expand his interest and involvement in international affairs, in 2003 Mahama became a member of the Pan-African Parliament, serving as the Chairperson of the West African Caucus until 2011. He was also a member of European and Pan African Parliaments' Ad-hoc Committee on Cooperation.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> In 2005 he was, additionally, appointed the Minority Spokesman for Foreign Affairs. He is a member of the [[UNDP]] Advisory Committee on [[Conflict Resolution]] in Ghana.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nOn 7 January 2009, Mahama became the [[Vice-President of Ghana]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://people.peacefmonline.com/profiles/245/biography/ |title=John Mahama Biography |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728052946/http://people.peacefmonline.com/profiles/245/biography/ |archivedate=28 July 2012 }}</ref> He also served as the Chairman of the National Economic Management Team, the [[Armed Forces Council]] of Ghana, the Decentralisation and Implementation Committee and the Police Council of Ghana in this capacity.\n\n=== As President ===\nIn line with [[Constitution of Ghana|Ghana's constitution]], Mahama became President of Ghana on 24 July 2012 on the death of his predecessor, [[John Atta Mills]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-18972107 |title=Ghana's President John Atta Mills dies |publisher=BBC News |date=24 July 2012 |accessdate=24 July 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724184729/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-18972107 |archivedate=24 July 2012 }}</ref> In July 2012, he became the Ghana's first president to have served at all levels of political office (Ghanaian and Pan-African [[Member of Parliament|MP]], Deputy Minister, [[Minister (government)|Minister]], Vice-President and President). He said in parliament upon being sworn in:\n<blockquote>This is the saddest day in our nation's history. Tears have engulfed our nation and we are deeply saddened and distraught and I'm personally devastated, I've lost a father, I've lost a friend, I've lost a mentor and a senior comrade. Ghana is united in grief at this time for our departed president.<ref name=aljaz>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2012/07/20127259518486684.html |title=Ghana swears in Mahama as new president |work=Al Jazeera |date=25 July 2012 |accessdate=25 July 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726095044/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2012/07/20127259518486684.html |archivedate=26 July 2012 }}</ref></blockquote>\n[[File:Secretary Kerry Meets With Ghanaian President Mahama (9942939153).jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[President of Ghana]] John Mahama holds a [[Bilateralism|bilateral]] [[meeting]] with the [[United States Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]].]]\nAs a result of his elevation to the presidency, Mahama made political history by becoming the first [[List of heads of state of Ghana|Ghanaian head of state]] to have been born after Ghana's [[declaration of independence]] on 6 March 1957{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}https://www.johnmahama.org/biography/. The National Democratic Congress (NDC) held a Special National Delegates Congress on 30 August 2012 and endorsed President John Dramani Mahama as its 2012 presidential candidate. President Mahama, the sole candidate of the party, polled 2, 767 votes, representing 99.5% of total votes cast, to pick the slot for the party.<ref name=\"ndc endorses president mahama as 2012 presidential candidate\">.He is recorded as the most corrupt president to Ghana since independence with corruption scandals such as GYEEDA,SUBA,SADA,BUS BRANDING,WOYOME,AMERI POWER DEAL,KARPOWER DEAL,AKOMFEM FLYING TO BURKINA FASO,FORD EXPEDITION ,KUMASI AIRPORT RUNWAY SCANDAL several 100s of high profile corruptions deals under his regime.\nDuring his regime,he only relocates corrupt officials to the office of the president as punishment.He used inflated contracts as means to siphon billion of dollars of state funds into personal accounts.\n{{cite web |url=http://www.allghananews.com/politics/5110-ndc-endorses-president-mahama-as-2012-presidential-candidate |title=ALL GHANA NEWS - My bid for President is no melodrama-Akpaloo |author=GNA |work=allghananews.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112122741/http://www.allghananews.com/politics/5110-ndc-endorses-president-mahama-as-2012-presidential-candidate |archivedate=12 November 2014 |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> Mahama has stated that his administration is deeply committed to continuing the [[Better Ghana Agenda]] started under President Mills.\n\nMahama won the [[2016 Ghanaian general election|December 2012 general election]] with 50.70% of the total valid votes cast and a 3% winning margin beating his nearest rival, [[Nana Akufo-Addo]] of the main opposition [[New Patriotic Party]], who polled a close 47.74%.  This was just barely enough to win the presidency without the need for a runoff.<ref name=autogenerated5 /> In addition, Mahama won the majority of valid votes cast in eight out of Ghana's ten administrative regions. Thirteen African Heads of State, one Prime Minister, two Vice-Presidents and 18 government delegations across the world attended his inaugural ceremony at the [[Black Star Square]] in [[Accra]] on 7 January 2013, when Mahama was sworn-in to begin his own four-year term.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201212/99293.php |title=11 Heads of States to attend Mahama's inauguration |author=Michael Ofori Amanfo Boateng |work=myjoyonline.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222102/http://edition.myjoyonline.com/pages/news/201212/99293.php |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAfter his investiture, the opposition [[New Patriotic Party]] led by its 2012 presidential candidate [[Nana Akufo-Addo]], running mate Dr [[Mahamudu Bawumia]] and the party chairman [[Jacob Otanka Obetsebi-Lamptey]], challenged the election results, alleging irregularities, malpractices, omissions and violations. The petition was heard by nine justices of the [[Supreme Court of Ghana]]. After eight months of hearing, the Court on 29 August 2013 dismissed the petition by a majority opinion.<ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\nMahama is one of Africa\u2019s most-followed leaders on the social networking sites, [[Twitter]] and [[Facebook]].<ref>{{Citation\n |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21434229 \n |title=African Viewpoint: Which leaders are Twitter savvy? \n |publisher=BBC News \n |location=United Kingdom \n |date=13 February 2013 \n |url-status=live \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130321204958/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-21434229 \n |archivedate=21 March 2013 \n}}</ref> In May 2013, he stated that all of West Africa is under the threat of Islamist militancy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-22714242 |title=Militants threaten 'all West Africa' |newspaper=BBC News |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822235924/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-22714242 |archivedate=22 August 2016 |date=30 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2014, he was elected to preside over [[ECOWAS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/03/30/mahama-named-west-african-bloc-head |title=Mahama named West African bloc head |work=News |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511020255/http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/03/30/mahama-named-west-african-bloc-head |archivedate=11 May 2015 }}</ref> On 26 June 2014, he was elected Chairperson of the [[African Union]]\u2019s (AU\u2019s) High-Level African Trade Committee (HATC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2014/June-27th/prez-mahama-takes-over-from-idris-derby-as-aus-trade-committee-chair.php |title=Ghana News - Prez Mahama takes over from Idris Derby as AU's Trade Committee Chair |work=myjoyonline.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014105156/http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2014/June-27th/prez-mahama-takes-over-from-idris-derby-as-aus-trade-committee-chair.php |archivedate=14 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 January 2016 on the occasion of the World Economic Forum in Davos, Mahama became co-chair of the Sustainable Development Goals Advocates group which consists of 17 eminent persons assisting the UN Secretary-General in the campaign to achieve the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) that world leaders unanimously adopted in September 2015. With a mandate to support the Secretary-General in his efforts to generate momentum and commitment to achieve the SDGs by 2030, the SDG Advocates have been working to promote the universal sustainable development agenda, to raise awareness of the integrated nature of the SDGs, and to foster the engagement of new stakeholders in the implementation of these Goals.<ref>[https://www.un.org/sustainabledevelopment/sdgadvocates/#who Sustainable Development Goals Advocates] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331061653/http://www.un.org/sustainabledevelopment/sdgadvocates/ |date=31 March 2016 }}. Un.org. Retrieved on 2017-02-05.</ref>\n\nOn 9 December 2016, Mahama was defeated by the main opposition leader [[Nana Akufo-Addo]], to whom he conceded defeat earlier that day. Mahama polled 44.4% of the valid votes cast compared to Akufo-Addo's 53.5%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/12/ghana-akufo-addo-wins-presidential-election-161209172455364.html |title=Ghana: Akufo-Addo wins presidential election |accessdate=16 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161216012923/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/12/ghana-akufo-addo-wins-presidential-election-161209172455364.html |archivedate=16 December 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, he was part of part of the [[ECOWAS]] mediation team to resolve the post-election political impasse in [[The Gambia]] between the defeated incumbent, [[Yahya Jammeh]] and declared winner, [[Adama Barrow|Adam Barrow]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/lifestyle/2017/February-19th/happy-to-be-part-of-the-gambia-success-mahama.php |title=Happy to be part of The Gambia success - Mahama |last=Myjoyonline.com |date=2017-02-19 |access-date=2017-02-21 |language=en-US |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222052854/http://www.myjoyonline.com/lifestyle/2017/February-19th/happy-to-be-part-of-the-gambia-success-mahama.php |archivedate=22 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citifmonline.com/2017/02/19/our-success-in-the-gambia-signifies-ecowas-relevance-mahama/ |title=Our success in The Gambia signifies ECOWAS' relevance \u2013 Mahama |last=Ansah |first=Marian Efe |date=2017-02-19 |website=Ghana News |access-date=2017-02-21 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222055713/https://citifmonline.com/2017/02/19/our-success-in-the-gambia-signifies-ecowas-relevance-mahama/ |archivedate=22 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mobile.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Gambia-has-given-true-meaning-to-relevance-of-ECOWAS-Mahama-511592 |title=Gambia has given true meaning to relevance of ECOWAS - Mahama |website=mobile.ghanaweb.com |language=en |access-date=2017-02-21 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222053455/http://mobile.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Gambia-has-given-true-meaning-to-relevance-of-ECOWAS-Mahama-511592 |archivedate=22 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and interests==\n[[File:Lordina Dramani Mahama (cropped).jpg|thumb|150px|Ghanaian [[First Lady]] Lordina Mahama on 3 June 2014.]]\nMahama is married to [[Lordina Mahama]] (n\u00e9e Effah, 6 March 1963). Mahama has five children named Shafik, Shahid, Sharaf, Jesse and Farida. He is a [[Christians|Christian]], born and raised a [[Presbyterian]] but is now a member of the [[Assemblies of God]], Ghana by marriage.<ref name=bio/>  His family is multi-faith, consisting of Christians and [[Muslim]]s.<ref name=\"Sworn in as new\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20131002102354/http://www.gbcghana.com/index.php?id=1.977333 John Dramani Mahama Sworn-in As New President of Ghana, Calls For Unity Among Ghanaians], at the [[Ghana Broadcasting Corporation]]; published July 24, 2012; archived at [[archive.org]] October 2, 2013</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://gbcghana.com/index.php?launch=candidates_profile |title=Profile of Presidential Candidates\n |publisher=Ghana Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=16 December 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202203917/http://gbcghana.com/index.php?launch=candidates_profile |archivedate=2 February 2014 }}</ref>  Being a staunch campaigner for sustainability, he has a keen interest in environmental affairs, particularly the problem of [[single-use]] [[plastic pollution|plastic waste]] pollution in Africa, which he committed himself to addressing during his tenure as Vice President.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gbcghana.com/index.php/id=1.346245 |title=Govt committed to eliminating plastic waste-Veep |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002103046/http://www.gbcghana.com/index.php/id%3D1.346245 |archivedate=2 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOver the course of his career, Mahama has written for several newspapers and other publications both locally and internationally. As a [[Member of Parliament|Parliamentarian]], Mahama wrote ''Mahama's Hammer'', a semi-regular column in a Ghanaian newspaper. His essays have also been published in the ''[[Daily Graphic (Ghana)|Daily Graphic]]'', ''[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]'', ''[[Huffington Post]]'', the ''[[Louisville Courier-Journal]]'', the ''[[New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]]''.<ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebony.com/news-views/bring-back-our-girls-african-heads-of-state-send-support-to-nigeria-304#.axzz31cRnVxcy |title=BRING BACK OUR GIRLS: African Heads of State Send Support to Nigeria |work=EBONY |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906093749/http://www.ebony.com/news-views/bring-back-our-girls-african-heads-of-state-send-support-to-nigeria-304 |archivedate=6 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebony.com/news-views/slaughtered-boys-missing-girls-who-stands-up-for-african-children#.U2ttyqKs9sX |title=Slaughtered Boys, Missing Girls: Who Stands Up for African Children? |work=EBONY |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906061603/http://www.ebony.com/news-views/slaughtered-boys-missing-girls-who-stands-up-for-african-children |archivedate=6 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://graphic.com.gh/features/opinion/22123-what-you-don-t-know.html |title=President Mahama writes: What you don't know |work=graphic.com.gh |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233504/http://www.graphic.com.gh/features/opinion/22123-what-you-don-t-know.html |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://nytimes.com/2013/12/06/opinion/mahama-mandela-taught-a-continent-to-forgive.html |work=The New York Times |title=Mandela Taught a Continent to Forgive |date=5 December 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131209072934/http://www.nytimes.com//2013/12/06/opinion/mahama-mandela-taught-a-continent-to-forgive.html |archivedate=9 December 2013 }}</ref> Additionally, he was a featured speaker at the [[TEDx]] [[Great Pacific Garbage Patch]] [[Academic conference|Conference]] in [[Santa Monica]].<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Mahama is also a devotee of [[Afrobeat|Afrobeat music]], especially that of [[Fela Kuti]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/321487/ghanas-mahama-writer-music-fan-and-president-elect |title=Ghana's Mahama: writer, music fan and president-elect - Inquirer News |author=Agence France-Presse |work=inquirer.net |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304023600/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/321487/ghanas-mahama-writer-music-fan-and-president-elect |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref>  Apart from his hobby of reading, Mahama also has a passionate interest in innovation particularly the use of [[technology]] in agriculture being a farmer himself. In particular, he is interested in finding the most effective ways to improve agricultural productivity and works to encourage more young people to see farming as a viable business and not a subsistence activity. This has translated into his passion to see the Savanna Accelerated Development Authority (SADA) create new opportunities for people living in the Savanna areas of the country, which includes the three Northern Regions, and the [[Volta Region|Volta]] Region. Even on official assignments outside of country, Mahama likes to take advantage of opportunities to visit agricultural establishments and update himself on current trends and developments. He also takes keen interest in the opportunities for simplifying and making tasks easier with the use of [[information and communications technology]], and considers the [[Information and communication technologies|ICT]] industry one of the sectors that can play a significant role in economic transformation and job creation.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> He's an avid fan of motor biking and owns about 5 of them.\n\n===Books===\nMahama's first book, a memoir called [[''My First Coup d'\u00c9tat: Memories from the Lost Decades of Africa'']], was published by [[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]] on 3 July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.modernghana.com/news/434142/1/a-vote-for-john-mahama-is-an-endorsement-of-corrup.html |title=A Vote For John Mahama Is An Endorsement Of Corruption\u2014NPP Germany|accessdate=2013-01-31 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206041658/http://www.modernghana.com/news/434142/1/a-vote-for-john-mahama-is-an-endorsement-of-corrup.html |archivedate=6 February 2013 }}. ''[[Amazon.com]].''</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theroot.com/views/ghana-s-new-leader-talks-africa-s-future |title=My First Coup D'Etat: Memoir Sheds Light on the Lost Decades |author=Akoto Ofori-Atta |date=24 July 2012 |work=The Root |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022204651/http://www.theroot.com/views/ghana-s-new-leader-talks-africa-s-future |archivedate=22 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/07/17/156506719/african-politics-and-afros-in-my-first-coup-detat |title=African Politics, And Afros, In 'My First Coup D'Etat' |date=17 July 2012 |work=NPR.org |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618172042/http://www.npr.org/2012/07/17/156506719/african-politics-and-afros-in-my-first-coup-detat |archivedate=18 June 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-10-12-book-review-my-first-coup-dtat-by-ghanas-accidental-president |title=Book review: My First Coup d'Etat, by Ghana's accidental president |work=dailymaverick.co.za |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618151333/http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2012-10-12-book-review-my-first-coup-dtat-by-ghanas-accidental-president |archivedate=18 June 2015 }}</ref> The most promising son of an [[affluent]] government minister, he spends his childhood shuttling in his father's [[chauffeur]]-driven cars, from his elite boarding school [[Achimota School]] in Accra to his many [[home]]s. He recalls in its first chapter the day in 1966 when he learned of the ousting of Ghana's founding president, [[Kwame Nkrumah]], in a military coup: \"When I look back on my life it's clear to me that this moment marked the awakening of my consciousness. It changed my life and influenced all the moments that followed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starafrica.com/en/news/detail-news/view/mahama-writer-historian-and-ghanas-ne-244519.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130203030428/http://www.starafrica.com/en/news/detail-news/view/mahama-writer-historian-and-ghanas-ne-244519.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 February 2013 |title=Mahama: writer, historian and Ghana's new president \u00bb politics \u00bb News - StarAfrica.com - News \u2013 StarAfrica.com |work=Starafrica |accessdate=5 June 2015 }}</ref>{{clear}}\n\n===Corruption allegations===\nIt was revealed in 2016 that Mahama accepted a [[Ford Expedition]] from a construction firm bidding for a lucrative government contract in 2012, while he was serving as Vice President. The Burkinabe contractor who had previously constructed a wall at the Ghanaian Embassy in Ouagadougou was at the time looking to get a road-building contract in Ghana's Volta region; this contractor later secured the contract but the vehicle left by the ex president for Government use.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://citifmonline.com/2016/09/29/full-text-chrajs-report-on-mahamas-ford-gift-saga/|title=Full Text: CHRAJ's report on Mahama's Ford gift saga - Ghana News|date=2016-09-29|work=Ghana News|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918064321/http://citifmonline.com/2016/09/29/full-text-chrajs-report-on-mahamas-ford-gift-saga/|archivedate=18 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|title=Election 2016: Seven scandals that rocked the NDC under John Mahama|last=Staff|first=Pulse|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104164708/http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|archivedate=4 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|title=Election 2016: Seven scandals that rocked the NDC under John Mahama|last=Staff|first=Pulse|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104164708/http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|archivedate=4 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Under Mahama's presidency in 2014, massive corruption was discovered at Ghana\u2019s Savannah Accelerated Development Authority (SADA). The authority had misappropriated millions of dollars allocated to it. SADA paid GH\u20b532,498,000 to ACICL, a business owned by Ghana's Roland Agambire, Mahama's close confidante, to plant five million trees in the savannah zone, but could only account for about 700,000 trees. It was also discovered that SADA spent GH\u00a215 million on guinea fowl, but could only account for a few of the birds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/opinion/2014/April-15th/manassehs-folder-the-sad-sada-story-of-northern-ghanas-elite.php|title=Manasseh's Folder: The sad SADA story of northern Ghana's elite - MyJoyOnline.com|website=www.myjoyonline.com|access-date=2017-12-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017193749/http://www.myjoyonline.com/opinion/2014/April-15th/manassehs-folder-the-sad-sada-story-of-northern-ghanas-elite.php|archivedate=17 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|title=Election 2016: Seven scandals that rocked the NDC under John Mahama|last=Staff|first=Pulse|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104164708/http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|archivedate=4 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2015 it was again discovered that the contract for the rebranding of 116 Metro Mass Transit (MMT) buses at a cost of Gh\u20b53,600,000 was sole sourced and awarded to a company named \u201c''Smarttys,''\u201d owned by a member of the ruling NDC activist Selassie Ibrahim. It was revealed that the rebranding of the buses cost the government Gh\u20b53,600,000 which at the time was more than the cost of the 116 buses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|title=Election 2016: Seven scandals that rocked the NDC under John Mahama|last=Staff|first=Pulse|access-date=2017-12-19|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104164708/http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/election-2016-seven-scandals-that-rocked-the-ndc-under-john-mahama-id5894854.html|archivedate=4 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Honours and awards===\n[[File:John Dramani Mahama UNDP 2010.jpg|thumb|right|195px|John Dramani Mahama at the UNDP in 2010]]\nMahama received an [[honorary doctorate]] in the field of [[Public Administration]], from the [[Ekiti State]] University of [[Nigeria]], formerly affiliated to the [[Obafemi Awolowo]] University in \"recognition of his politico-socio economic development of Ghana and Africa at various stages of his political career.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gbcghana.com/index.php?launch=gallery&id=1.843195 |title=KITNES Page Error |accessdate=16 December 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220180128/http://www.gbcghana.com/index.php?launch=gallery&id=1.843195 |archivedate=20 December 2016 }}</ref> Later the same university passed a resolution to name its [[Faculty (division)|Faculty]] of [[Management Science]] after him.<ref>[http://www.myradiogoldlive.com/index.php/general-news/3400-nigerian-university-to-name-faculty-after-president-mahama Nigerian University to Name Faculty after President Mahama<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317045345/http://www.myradiogoldlive.com/index.php/general-news/3400-nigerian-university-to-name-faculty-after-president-mahama |date=17 March 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Cuba]]n government, recognising Mahama's relentless advocacy for the Cuban cause, namely for the lifting of the 50-year economic embargo on the communist country and for the freedom of the detained Cuban five by the United States government, conferred on him the Friendship Medal.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://iamaghanaian.com/index.php?do=/news/vice-president-john-mahama-honoured/ |title=Vice President John Mahama Honoured |author=phpFox |work=iamaghanaian.com |accessdate=5 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317032332/http://iamaghanaian.com/index.php?do=%2Fnews%2Fvice-president-john-mahama-honoured%2F |archivedate=17 March 2014 }}</ref> {{citation needed|date=September 2017}}The General Council of [[Assemblies of God]], Ghana honoured Mahama with its Daniel Award.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130124123411/http://www.gbcghana.com/new/index.php?id=1.749979 GBC News, Vice President John Mahama honoured for exceptional leadership qualities<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The Graduate School of Governance and Leadership also awarded him the African Servant Leadership Award while the Institute of Public Relations recognized Mahama with a prize for his leadership acumen and technocratic flair.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> In 2013, the Forum for Agricultural Research in Africa (FARA) conferred on Mahama the Africa Award for Excellence in Food Security and Poverty Reduction.<ref>\n{{Cite web |url=http://www.tv3network.com/Business/veep-calls-for-more-support-for-the-agric-sector.html |title=Veep calls for more support for the agric sector &#124; Business<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=14 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814015438/http://tv3network.com/Business/veep-calls-for-more-support-for-the-agric-sector.html |archive-date=14 August 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }} \n</ref> In March 2016, [[University of Aberdeen]] held a special convocation to confer an honorary degree of Doctors of Laws (LLD) on President John Mahama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2016/March-17th/mahama-gets-honorary-law-degree-from-aberdeen-university.php |title=Mahama gets honorary law degree from Aberdeen University - MyJoyOnline |last=Myjoyonline.com |accessdate=16 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525045211/http://www.myjoyonline.com/news/2016/March-17th/mahama-gets-honorary-law-degree-from-aberdeen-university.php |archivedate=25 May 2016 }}</ref>\n\nMahama has also attended numerous conferences and won many fellowships, including a study as a [[visiting scholar]] at [[The Johns Hopkins University]], [[Baltimore]], United States. He is also a [[Bill Gates]] Fellow.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> He was awarded the Great Cross of the National Order of [[Benin]], the highest award in Benin, by President [[Yayi Boni]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghana.gov.gh/index.php/news-slider/2958-president-mahama-receives-national-order-of-benin |title=GHANA HOSTS INTERNATIONAL SYMPOSIUM ON THE ROLE OF REGULATION IN ICT DEVELOPMENT - Government of Ghana |first=Sule |last=Jotie |accessdate=16 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805143616/http://www.ghana.gov.gh/index.php/news-slider/2958-president-mahama-receives-national-order-of-benin |archivedate=5 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Mahama received the 2016 African Political Leader of the Year Award from the African Leadership Magazine in [[South Africa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citifmonline.com/2017/02/23/mahama-to-deliver-keynote-speech-at-african-leadership-magazine-awards/ |title=Mahama to deliver keynote speech at African Leadership Magazine awards |last=Adogla-Bessa |first=Delali |date=2017-02-23 |website=Ghana News |access-date=2017-02-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223084229/http://citifmonline.com/2017/02/23/mahama-to-deliver-keynote-speech-at-african-leadership-magazine-awards/ |archivedate=23 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pulse.com.gh/politics/congratulations-mahama-named-2016-best-african-political-leader-id6268121.html |title=Congratulations: Mahama named 2016 best African Political leader |last=Tornyi |first=Emmanuel |access-date=2017-02-23 |language=en-US |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224055607/http://pulse.com.gh/politics/congratulations-mahama-named-2016-best-african-political-leader-id6268121.html |archivedate=24 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://starrfmonline.com/?p=13321 |title=Mahama wins African Political Leader of the Year Award |date=2017-02-23 |newspaper=Starr Fm |access-date=2017-02-23 |language=en-US |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223065433/http://starrfmonline.com/?p=13321 |archivedate=23 February 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://medafricatimes.com/12073-ex-ghana-president-mahama-wins-africa-leadership-award.html |title=Ex-Ghana president Mahama wins Africa leadership award {{!}} Medafrica Times |website=medafricatimes.com |language=en-US |access-date=2017-02-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301180829/http://medafricatimes.com/12073-ex-ghana-president-mahama-wins-africa-leadership-award.html |archivedate=1 March 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/John-Mahama-s-keynote-address-at-2016-African-Leadership-Magazine-Person-of-the-Year-Awards-513166 |title=John Mahama's keynote address at 2016 African Leadership Magazine Person of the Year Awards |website=www.ghanaweb.com |access-date=2017-02-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301181700/http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/John-Mahama-s-keynote-address-at-2016-African-Leadership-Magazine-Person-of-the-Year-Awards-513166 |archivedate=1 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.johnmahama.org/}}\n* {{C-SPAN|John Mahama}}\n* {{commons-inline|Category:John Dramani Mahama|John Dramani Mahama}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gh}}\n{{s-bef|before=Mahama Jeduah}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Bole (Ghana parliament constituency)|Bole]]|years=1997\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=Joseph Akati Saaka}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ekwow Spio-Garbrah]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Communications (Ghana)|Minister for Communications]]|years=1998\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|af