{"title_page": "Thank U, Next", "text_new": "{{About|the album|its title track|Thank U, Next (song)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Short description|2019 studio album by Ariana Grande}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Thank U, Next\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Ariana Grande]]\n| cover        = Thank U, Next album cover.png\n| caption      = Digital, streaming, and Japanese deluxe edition cover; the border is colored black instead of pink on the standard physical edition<ref name=\"iTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/thank-u-next/1450330588|title=thank u, next by Ariana Grande on Apple Music|website=[[Apple Music]]|accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Amazon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07N37VTFY/|title=Ariana Grande \u2013 thank u, next|publisher=Amazon|date=January 25, 2019|accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref>\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2019|2|8}}\n| recorded     = October\u2013December 2018<ref name=\"October 2018 recording\">{{Cite web|last=Maicki|first=Salvatore|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/10/02/ariana-grande-back-in-studio-mystery-tracklist-sweetener|title=Ariana Grande is back in the studio working on new music|work=[[The Fader]]|date=October 2, 2018|accessdate=November 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bigtop40.com/news/ariana-grande-new-album-release-republic/|title=Ariana Grande hints new album is ready but her record label won't release it|work=Big Top 40|date=December 5, 2018|accessdate=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| studio       = {{Collapsible list|title=Various|[[Jungle City Studios|Jungle City]], Right Track|(New York City, New York)|MXM, [[Conway Recording Studios|Conway]]|(Los Angeles, California)|[[Record Plant|The Record Plant]]|(Hollywood, California)|Wolf Cousins|(Stockholm, Sweden)|Entierty|(London, England)}}\n| genre        = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Trap music|trap]]}}\n| length       = 41:11\n| label        = [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| producer     = \n* [[Ariana Grande]]\n* [[Scooter Braun]]\n* [[Social House|Charles Anderson]]\n* Brian Baptiste\n* [[Tommy Brown (record producer)|Tommy Brown]]\n* [[Social House|Michael Foster]]\n* [[Ilya Salmanzadeh|Ilya]]\n* [[Max Martin]]\n* Happy Perez\n* [[Pop Wansel]]\n| prev_title   = [[Sweetener (album)|Sweetener]]\n| prev_year    = 2018\n| next_title   = [[K Bye for Now (SWT Live)]]\n| next_year    = 2019\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Thank U, Next\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Thank U, Next (song)|Thank U, Next]]\n | single1date = November 3, 2018\n | single2     = [[7 Rings]]\n | single2date = January 18, 2019\n | single3     = [[Break Up with Your Girlfriend, I'm Bored]]\n | single3date = February 8, 2019\n}}\n}}\n'''''Thank U, Next''''' (stylized in [[Letter case#All lowercase|all lowercase]]) is the fifth [[studio album]] by American singer [[Ariana Grande]], released on February 8, 2019, by [[Republic Records]].<ref>{{cite tweet|author=[[Ariana Grande|Grande, Ariana]]|user=ArianaGrande|number=1088146538029670400|title=feb 8|date=January 23, 2019|accessdate=January 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Blistein|first=Jon|title=Ariana Grande Details ''Thank U, Next'' Track List, Release Date|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-track-list-782761/|accessdate=January 23, 2019|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=January 22, 2019|location=United States}}</ref> Following the release of her previous studio album [[Sweetener (album)|''Sweetener'']] (2018), Grande began working on a new album in October of the same year, enlisting writers and producers such as [[Tommy Brown (record producer)|Tommy Brown]], [[Max Martin]], [[Ilya Salmanzadeh]] and [[Pop Wansel|Andrew \"Pop\" Wansel]]. The album was created in the midst of personal matters, including the death of former boyfriend [[Mac Miller]] and her break-up with fianc\u00e9 [[Pete Davidson]].\n\n''Thank U, Next'' was preceded by two singles, the  [[Thank U, Next (song)|title track]] and \"[[7 Rings]]\", both debuting atop the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart, becoming Grande's first and second number one single in the US, respectively. \"[[Break Up with Your Girlfriend, I'm Bored]]\" was released as the third single on the day of the album's release, peaking at number two on the Hot 100. In support of both ''Sweetener'' and ''Thank U, Next'', Grande embarked on the [[Sweetener World Tour]], beginning on March 18, 2019. The album peaked atop the charts of many countries, including Australia, Canada, Ireland, New Zealand, the United Kingdom and the United States. One month after its release, the album was certified [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), for moving one million [[album-equivalent units]] in the US.\n\nUpon its release, ''Thank U, Next'' received widespread acclaim from [[Music journalism|music critics]], with many praising its cohesiveness and production. It was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]] at the [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards]] while its second single, \"7 Rings\", was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]]. The album was ranked in several year-end and decade-end best music lists.\n\n==Background==\nIn September 2018, Grande's old friend and ex-boyfriend, rapper [[Mac Miller]], died from a drug overdose. The following month, Grande announced that she would take a break from music.<ref name=\"independent\">{{Cite web|last=Shepherd|first=Jack|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/ariana-grande-break-music-mac-miller-death-ex-boyfriend-sweetener-pete-davidson-a8579016.html|title=Ariana Grande confirms break from music following rapper Mac Miller's death|work=The Independent|date=October 11, 2018|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref> That same month, however, Grande revealed that she had been in the studio working on new music, and she announced the [[Sweetener World Tour]] (2019). She stated that the tour would support both her fourth studio album, [[Sweetener (album)|''Sweetener'']] (2018), and her upcoming fifth studio album.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Espinoza|first=Joshua|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/10/ariana-grande-back-in-the-studio-taking-time-off|title=Ariana Grande Is Back in the Studio After Taking Time Off|work=Complex|date=October 3, 2018|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Sippell|first=Margeaux|url=https://variety.com/2018/music/news/ariana-grande-announces-sweetener-world-tour-dates-1202994235|title=Ariana Grande Announces 'Sweetener World Tour' Dates|work=Variety|date=October 25, 2018|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref> Later in October 2018, Grande broke off her engagement with comedian [[Pete Davidson]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/entertainment/a20979533/ariana-grande-and-pete-davidson-a-timeline-of-their-relationship/|title=Ariana Grande and Pete Davidson: a timeline of their relationship|last=Bartram|first=Naomi|date=December 1, 2018|website=Cosmopolitan|access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Recording and production==\n[[File:Jungle City Studios.jpeg|right|thumbnail|The [[Jungle City Studios]] in New York City served as the album's main recording location.]]\n\nGrande started recording the album in October 2018, less than two months after the release of her previous album ''Sweetener''.<ref name=\"October 2018 recording\" /> It was mainly recorded at [[Jungle City Studios]] in [[New York City]], with additional recording locations including Right Track Studios in the same city, MXM and [[Conway Recording Studios]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[Record Plant|The Record Plant]] in [[Hollywood]], California, Wolf Cousins Studios in [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]], and Entirety Studios in [[London]], [[England]].<ref name=\"linernotes\"/>\n\nGrande opted to work with producers and songwriters she was already friends with, stating the decision \"kind of saved my life. It was kind of this super challenging chapter that sucked, and then my friends made it amazing and special.\"<ref name=\"billboard1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8497474/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-interview-zach-sang-show|title=Ariana Grande Says the 'Thank U, Next' Album 'Kind of Saved My Life' in In-Depth 'Zach Sang Show' Interview|last=Iasimone|first=Ashley|date=February 9, 2019|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> [[Tommy Brown (record producer)|Tommy Brown]] produced the most tracks with five, and collaborated on production with Charles Anderson and Michael Foster of [[Social House]] on two of them. Meanwhile, [[Max Martin]] and [[Ilya Salmanzadeh]] produced four tracks together.<ref name=\"theringer\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theringer.com/music/2019/2/9/18217813/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-album-review|title=Ariana Grande Just Beat the Boys by Joining Them|last=Harvilla|first=Rob|date=February 8, 2019|website=The Ringer|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSongwriter [[Victoria Mon\u00e9t]] said that Grande and her team worked quickly, writing and recording \"nine songs or so\" after one week. Unlike her previous albums, most recording sessions were finished after just two weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-ariana-grande-made-thank-u-next-album-792233/|title=Some Albums Take Years. Ariana Grande Made \u2018Thank U, Next\u2019 in 2 Weeks|last=Leight|first=Elias|date=2019-02-09|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> Grande's team always had [[champagne]] in the studio, notably [[Veuve Clicquot]], as later referenced in her collaboration with Mon\u00e9t, \"[[Monopoly (song)|Monopoly]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rmh_gVKJgE8|title=Victoria Mon\u00e9t \"MONOPOLY\" Official Lyrics & Meaning &#124; Verified|date=May 2, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref> Mon\u00e9t co-wrote six of the albums songs, including \"Ghostin\" which was the first song written for the album and took the longest to write.<ref name=\"Ariana answers\">{{cite web|last=Morin|first=Alyssa|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1013090/12-surprising-secrets-from-ariana-grande-s-thank-u-next-revealed|title=12 Surprising Secrets From Ariana Grande\u2019s Thank U, Next Revealed|date=February 8, 2019|accessdate=May 19, 2019|work=[[E! News]]}}</ref> Grande described it as the hardest song to write for the album and initially requested the song not be included on the final tracklisting.<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|publisher=Zach Sang|title=Ariana Grande \"thank u, next\" Interview|date=February 9, 2019|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fpl8v3jiuNU|via=[[YouTube]]|access-date=May 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n\n===Music and lyrics===\n{{Quote box\n |quote = \"I feel like there are certain standards that pop women are held to that men aren't. We have to do the teaser before the single, then do the single, and wait to do the pre-order, and radio has to impact before the video, and we have to do the discount on this day, and all this, and it's just like, 'Bruh, I just want to talk to my fans and sing and write music and drop it the way these boys do. Why do they get to make records like that and I don't?' So I do and I did and I am, and I will continue to.\" \n |source =&nbsp;\u2014 {{small|Grande on the album's lead single and production duration.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/women-in-music/8487877/ariana-grande-cover-story-billboard-women-in-music-2018|title= Billboard Woman of the Year Ariana Grande: 'There's Not Much I'm Afraid of Anymore'|magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date= December 5, 2018|accessdate= March 31, 2019}}</ref>}}\n |align = right\n |width = 35%\n |border = 1px\n |fontsize = 88%\n}}\n''Thank U, Next'' is a [[Pop music|pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[Trap music|trap]] album with many influences of [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] on its beats and productions.<ref name=\"AllMusic\" /><ref name=\"vulture\">{{cite web |last=Jenkins |first=Craig |title=Thank U, Next Is a Phoenix Moment for Ariana Grande |url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-album-review.html |website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|Vulture]] |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"spin\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/02/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-review/|title=Ariana Grande\u2019s thank u, next Is Perfect For the Moment|last=Gaca|first=Anna|date=February 14, 2019|website=SPIN|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"consequence\">{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/02/album-review-ariana-grande-thank-u-next/|title=Album of the Week: The Real Ariana Grande Arrives on the Authentic thank u, next|last=Graves|first=Wren|date=February 15, 2019|website=Consequence of Sound|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The 50 Best Albums of 2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/best-albums-2019-914750/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-3-914757/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=27 December 2019}}</ref> It explores a diversity of other music genres, including [[dancehall]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[pop-rap]] and many [[Urban contemporary|urban]] influences.<ref name=\"NME\" /> Rob Sheffield from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' stated the album \"''Thank U, Next'' is just a woman and a mood, taking that mood out for a drive until she pedal-to-the-metals it right off a cliff.\"<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/> In an interview with Zach Sang she said: \"We walked to the studio everyday, and just made music and it turned everything around in my life. It sounds very corny but it was like, the most beautiful.\"<ref name=\"youtube\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fpl8v3jiuNU&t=2218s|title=Ariana Grande \"thank u, next\" Interview|last=|first=|date=February 9, 2019|publisher=Zach Sang|via=[[YouTube]]|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Songs and lyrical content===\n[[File:Rupaul Dragcon 2018-303 (41377494134).jpg|thumb|left|[[Shangela|Shangela Laquifa Wadley]], mononymously addressed as '''Shangela''' (pictured in 2018) has an uncredited feature on the third track \"[[NASA (Ariana Grande song)|NASA]]\".]]\n\nThe album begins with the song \"[[Imagine (Ariana Grande song)|Imagine]]\",<ref name=\"iTunes review\">{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/thank-u-next/1450330588|title=thank u, next|last=|first=|date=February 8, 2019|website=[[iTunes]]|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> an [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] [[ballad]] with a [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap]]-inspired rhythm.<ref name=\"people\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/music/ariana-grande-new-single-imagine/|title=Ariana Grande Releases Romantic New Song 'Imagine' \u2014 Here's Why Fans Think It's About Mac Miller|website=People.com|access-date=14 January 2019|quote=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blackboybulletin.com/2018/12/15/review-ariana-grande-nails-it-again-with-imagine/|title=Review: Ariana Grande Nails It Again With \"Imagine\" \u2013 black boy bulletin|website=Black Boy Bullentin|access-date=2018-12-15}}</ref> The song features multiple [[Whistle register|whistle notes]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hit.com.au/story/ariana-grande-brings-back-the-whistle-note-for-her-new-song-imagine-118028|title=Ariana Grande Brings Back The Whistle Note For Her New Song Imagine|date=14 December 2018|website=Hit|accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref> and its lyrics speak about Grande's denial of failed relationships.<ref name=\"billboard\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/ariana-grande-teases-new-song-imagine-about-failed-relationships/|title=Ariana Grande Teases New Song About 'Failed Relationships'|date=2018-12-12|website=Us Weekly|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> Mathew Rodriguez from ''Out'' mentioned that the song \"does the double duty of being both a great song and a great introduction.\"<ref name=\"out\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.out.com/entertainment/2019/2/08/ariana-grandes-thank-u-next-track-track-review|title=Ariana Grande\u2019s \u2018Thank U, Next\u2019: A Track-by-Track Review|website=Out|access-date=31 March 2019|quote=}}</ref> The next track \"[[Needy (song)|Needy]]\" is a [[mid-tempo]] minimalistic song with a metronome-like synth in the foreground.<ref name=\"medium\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@chloecrookshanks/track-by-track-review-ariana-grande-thank-u-next-eb5449338f13|title=Track by track review: Ariana Grande- \u2018thank u, next\u2019|website=Medium|access-date=31 March 2019|quote=}}</ref> Its lyrics are about Grande's insecurities in relationships.<ref name=\"out\" /> \"[[NASA (Ariana Grande song)|NASA]],\" named after the [[NASA|U.S. space agency of the same name]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2019/02/ariana-grande-nasa/582340/|title=A Space Nerd\u2019s Reading of Ariana Grande\u2019s \u2018NASA\u2019 Song|last=Koren|first=Marina|date=2019-02-09|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> is a \"bouncy-R&B tune.\"<ref name=\"RollingStone\" /> The track features a spoken introduction by [[Shangela]], an American [[drag queen]]. She says, \"One small step for woman, one giant leap for womankind\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/music/a26254894/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-album-numbers/|title=A Breakdown of Literally Every Single Thing That Happens On Ariana's New Album, 'Thank U, Next'|first=Hannah|last=Chambers|date=8 February 2019|website=Cosmopolitan|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> a variation on [[Neil Armstrong]]'s quote, \"That's one small step for a man, one giant leap for mankind.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/art-books-music/a26246260/ariana-grande-nasa-lyrics-meaning/|title=Ariana Grande's \"NASA\" Is the Anthem for People Who Need Space|last=Gonzales|first=Erica|date=2019-02-08|website=Harper's BAZAAR|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> Carolyn Bernucca of ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' said, \"The standout track, 'NASA,' is punctuated by thumping bass and trap drums that have made their way from Atlanta all the way into mainstream pop.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/02/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-album-weve-always-wanted|title=\u2018Thank U, Next\u2019 Is the Ariana Grande Album We\u2019ve Always Wanted|website=Complex|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> The fourth track is \"[[Bloodline (Ariana Grande song)|Bloodline]].\" It is a [[reggae-pop]] song with [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] influences that contains brassy [[horn (instrument)|horn]]s and a pounding [[Bass (sound)|bass]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/music/a26305441/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-review/|title=Ariana Grande\u2019s Thank U, Next Is a Horny Emotions Album for the Ages|last=Tang|first=Estelle|date=February 19, 2019|website=Elle.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7696564/ariana-grande-drops-break-up-with-your-girlfriend-im-bored-video?chrome=1|title=Ariana Grande Drops \"Break Up With Your Girlfriend, I\u2019m Bored\" Video|last=Nied|first=Mike|date=February 8, 2019|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]}}</ref><ref name=\"abitofpopmusic\">{{Cite web|url=https://abitofpopmusic.com/2019/02/08/album-review-ariana-grande-thank-u-next-track-by-track/|title=Album Review: Ariana Grande \u2013 Thank U, Next (track by track)|last=Music|first=Michael|date=February 8, 2019|website=A Bit Of Pop Music}}</ref> It has been compared to Grande's 2016 single \"[[Side to Side]]\" and \"[[Greedy (Ariana Grande song)|Greedy]]\" from her third studio album, [[Dangerous Woman (album)|Dangerous Woman]].<ref name=\"abitofpopmusic\" /> The song features a sound bite from Marjorie Grande, Grande's grandmother, in which she is talking about a hearing aid.<ref name=\"youtube\" /> ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that the song \"posits the idea that maybe it\u2019s best to just see how things go relationship-wise and getting engaged after a few months isn\u2019t essential\", believing that this song is about [[Pete Davidson]].<ref name=\"Guardian\" />\n\n[[File:Victoria Mon\u00e9t1.jpg|thumb|right|[[Victoria Mon\u00e9t]] (pictured in 2017) co-wrote most of the songs on the album.]]\n\nThe fifth track of the record is \"Fake Smile\", a [[hip hop soul]]-inspired track with a trap groove.<ref name=\"RollingStone\" /> It features a [[Wendy Rene]] sample (as featured in tracks previously by Metro Boomin and [[Wu-Tang Clan]]).{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} Lyrically, the song is about the attack on her concert in Manchester and the death of ex-boyfriend Mac Miller, and the emotional toll that these events inflicted upon her.<ref name=\"msn\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-xl/northamerica/life-arts/ariana-grande-i%E2%80%99ve-been-through-hell/ar-BBOgB5e|title=Ariana Grande: I\u2019ve been through hell|last=Powell|first=Emma|date=October 11, 2018|website=MSN|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> Chloe Crookshanks from ''[[Medium (website)|Medium]]'' stated that the song is \"Weaved in with some funky muted bass, she states candidly her understandable disdain for putting on a show ('fuck a fake smile')\".<ref name=\"medium1\">{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@chloecrookshanks/track-by-track-review-ariana-grande-thank-u-next-eb5449338f13|title=Track by track review: Ariana Grande- \u2018thank u, next\u2019|last=Crooshanks|first=Chloe|date=February 14, 2019|website=Medium|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> \"Bad Idea\" is an [[Electronic dance music|EDM]] and trap number, beginning with an 80's rock-ballad intro that garnered comparison to [[David Guetta]]'s 2012 hit single \"[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]\" featuring [[Sia (musician)|Sia]].<ref name=\"elle\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/music/a26305441/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-review/|title=Ariana Grande\u2019s Thank U, Next Is a Horny Emotions Album for the Ages|last=Tang|first=Estelle|date=February 19, 2019|website=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2019/02/08/5-reasons-to-say-thank-u-for-ariana-grandes-new-album/ |title=5 reasons to say 'Thank U' for Ariana Grande's new album |last=Arnold |first=Chuck |date=February 8, 2019 |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |access-date=July 23, 2019}}</ref> With an orchestra throughout the bridge and outro,<ref name=\"elle1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/02/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-album-review-cold-truths/582376/|title=Ariana Grande Tells the Cold Truth on Thank U, Next|last=Kornhaber|first=Spencer|date=February 8, 2019|website=The Atlantic|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> its lyrics are about Grande's desire to numb her pain.<ref name=\"chimes\">{{Cite web|url=https://chimesnewspaper.com/43887/entertainment/thank-u-next-review-ariana-grande-bares-soul-in-latest-album/|title=\"thank u, next\" Review: Ariana Grande bares soul in latest album|last=Santos|first=Karla|date=February 14, 2019|website=Chimes|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> The seventh track \"Make Up\" is Grande's most sexually explicit song on the album, featuring many [[double entendre]]<nowiki/>s.<ref name=\"chimes\" /> It is a trap record with [[wonky pop]] and [[Bubblegum pop|bubblegum]] influences and it contains a \"rap-influenced bridge\".<ref name=\"chimes\" /> A Bit Of Pop Music wrote, \"she wants to fight with her partner only so they can make up later, while also wanting him to ruin her make up.\"<ref name=\"abitofpopmusic\" /> \"Ghostin\", the eighth track, is an emotional synth-and-strings ballad.<ref name=\"iTunes review\"/> Lyrically, it discusses Grande's last two relationships, stating that \"she should ghost the guy that still makes her cry and wants to stop hurting the person she is with now while he is being patient with her,\" being Miller and Davidson.<ref name=\"abitofpopmusic\" /> Savan Kotecha, who co-wrote the song with Grande, told ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' of working on the track: \"[When we were writing] 'Ghostin,' we were in New York... The song speaks for itself in terms of what it's about. We were with her for a week in New York witnessing that, witnessing her feelings on that.\"<ref name=\"rollingstone2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-savan-kotecha-interview-791280/|title=How Ariana Grande Scored Two Number One Albums in Just Six Months|last=Leight|first=Elias|date=February 18, 2019|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> ''NME'' stated that it was \"One of the record\u2019s most talked-about tracks\" and also \"one of the album\u2019s most devastating moments.\"<ref name=\"NME2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/ariana-grande-ghostin-mac-miller-pete-davidson-song-meaning-explained-2459226|title=Is Ariana Grande\u2019s \u2018Ghostin\u2019 about Mac Miller and Pete Davidson? The song\u2019s meaning explained|date=March 1, 2019|website=[[NME]]|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> According to Grande, she \"begged\" her manager, [[Scooter Braun]], to remove the track from the album, but he convinced her to keep it.<ref name=\"youtube\" />\n\n{{Listen\n|filename= Ariana Grande Thank U, Next.mp3\n|pos= left\n|title= \"Thank U, Next\"\n|description=Sample of the song \"[[Thank U, Next (song)|Thank U, Next]].\"}}\n\nThe ninth track \"[[In My Head (Ariana Grande song)|In My Head]]\" begins with an excerpt of a voicemail from by Grande's close friend Doug Middlebrook.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Weatherby |first1=Taylor |title=Behind the Intros On 'Thank U, Next': How Ariana Grande Featured Her Nonna, Her Best Friend and a 'Drag Race' Star |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8497321/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-intros-nonna-doug-middlebrook-shangela |accessdate=21 May 2019 |work=Billboard |date=8 February 2019}}</ref> It is a [[Trap music|trap-pop]] hybrid with many R&B influences.<ref name=\"abitofpopmusic\" /> ''Medium'' said that \"Grande addresses her failure to see people for who they truly are.\"<ref name=\"medium\" /> \"[[7 Rings]],\" the tenth track, is a trap-pop and R&B song.<ref>{{cite web|title=7 rings \u2013 Single by Ariana Grande|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/7-rings-single/1449165901|accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ew\">{{cite web |last=Nelson |first=Jeff |title=Ariana Grande reveals some of her favorite things in new women empowerment anthem '7 Rings' |url=https://ew.com/music/2019/01/18/ariana-grande-favorite-things-7-rings/ |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=January 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Kornhaber\" /> It features a heavy bass<ref name=\"Bling\" /> and sees Grande discuss \"how global success has allowed her to enjoy the finer things\".<ref name=\"Reilly\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-the-video-for-ariana-grandes-new-song-7-rings-2434822|title=Watch the video for Ariana Grande's new song '7 Rings'|last=Reilly|first=Nick|date=January 18, 2019|website=NME|accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref> [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] magazine noted it's \"the most hip-hop-leaning song Grande has released in the post-''[[Sweetener (album)|Sweetener]]'' era yet, with Grande almost rapping the song's verses\".<ref name=\"Bling\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8494008/ariana-grande-7-rings-video|title=Ariana Grande & Her Girlfriends Get Their Bling On In Sassy '7 Rings' Video: Watch|website=Billboard|accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"[[Thank U, Next (song)|Thank U, Next]]\" is the eleventh track on the album. A [[Empowerment|self-empowerment]] pop and R&B song with elements of [[synth-pop]],  its lyrics discuss many of Grande's past relationships.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2018/11/song-of-the-week-ariana-grande-thank-u-next/|title=Song of the Week: Ariana Grande Moves on with Style in \"thank u, next\"|first=Clara|last=Scott|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=November 9, 2018|accessdate=November 15, 2018|quote=\"Her new release, 'thank u, next', is a pure pop banger in every sense of the phrase...\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2021727/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-pete-davidson-2/franchise/the-week-in-pop|title= Ariana Grande's \"thank u, next\" Is Social Media As Pop|work=[[Stereogum]]|last=DeVille|first=Chris|date=November 8, 2018|accessdate=November 18, 2018|quote=a largely straightforward '90s-inspired R&B-pop tune}}</ref><ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande Releases New Song 'Thank U, Next' Just Before 'SNL'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8483083/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-song|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=November 3, 2018|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Single Review: Ariana Grande \u2013 Thank U, Next|url=https://abitofpopmusic.com/2018/11/04/single-review-ariana-grande-thank-u-next/|website=A Bit Of Pop Music|date=November 4, 2018|accessdate=November 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande's 'Thank U, Next' Proves She's a New Kind of Pop Star|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/ariana-grande-breathin-thank-u-next-pop-charts-754240/|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=November 9, 2018|accessdate=November 10, 2018}}</ref> Grande explained in an interview that \"thank u, next...\" is a phrase that she and fellow singer/songwriter [[Victoria Mon\u00e9t]] use.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande Is Back in the Studio After Taking Time Off|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/10/ariana-grande-back-in-the-studio-taking-time-off|website=Complex|date=October 4, 2018|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref> Markos Papadatos from ''Digital Journal'' said the song is an \"ode to gratitude, an anthem to a fresh start and new beginnings, where she is not afraid to be raw and vulnerable; Grande's vulnerability is the listener's reward.\" He also said the song is \"sultry, cathartic and expressive\" and praised Grande's breathy vocals as \"pristine and heavenly, and it is evident the pop throne is still hers. 'thank u, next' garners an A rating.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/review-ariana-grande-releases-empowering-new-single-thank-u-next/article/536129|title=Review: Ariana Grande releases empowering new single 'thank u, next' (Includes first-hand account)|date=November 4, 2018|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> The final track \"[[Break Up with Your Girlfriend, I'm Bored]]\" is a trap-pop and R&B song.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/columns/pop/8499607/ariana-grande-sweetener-thank-u-next-combined-edit|title='Sweet, Thanks': Combining Ariana Grande's Two Recent LPs Into One 13-Track Masterpiece|last=Unterberger|first=Andrew|website=Billboard|date=22 February 2019|access-date=22 February 2019|quote=An ideal radio single that throws back to the turn of the century with [...] its impeccable pop-R&B hybridity.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/feb/16/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-review|title=Ariana Grande: Thank U, Next review \u2013 a lodestar for how complicated life can be|last=Empire|first=Kitty|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=17 February 2019|access-date=18 March 2019|quote= Break Up With Your Girlfriend, I\u2019m Bored \u2013 a trap-pop entreaty that paints Grande as a bad girl, trying to steal someone else\u2019s man.}}</ref> It was said to be Grande's most eye-catching song from the album.<ref name=\"abitofpopmusic\" /> The track replaced \"Remember\", a song previously planned to be on the album, but was too personal for Grande to release.<ref>{{cite web|last=Abraham|first=Mya|url=https://www.bet.com/music/2019/02/08/ariana-grande-mac-miller-ghostin-reactions.html|title=One Of Ariana Grande's Newest Songs Is Another Ode To Mac Miller...|date=February 8, 2019|accessdate=April 17, 2019|publisher=[[BET]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/arianagrande/status/1084558806758023168?lang=en|title=i added a fun one (lol) to replace one that i decided i don\u2019t think wanna share w the world. so we back to twelve tracks. i appreciate u understanding in advance.|last=Grande|first=Ariana|date=2019-01-13|website=@arianagrande|access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref> It samples \"It Makes Me Ill\" by [[NSYNC]] in the bridge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/ariana-grande-break-up-with-you-girlfriend-im-bored-791762/|title=Watch Ariana Grande Party in \u2018Break Up With Your Girlfriend I\u2019m Bored\u2019 Video|last=Spanos|first=Brittany|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=8 February 2019|access-date=31 March 2019|quote=}}</ref> ''Medium'' states that \"Ariana's to lift the energy, injecting a sense of sensuality, playfulness and questionable behaviour.\"<ref name=\"medium\" />\n\n==Release and promotion==\n''Thank U, Next'' was released worldwide on February 8, 2019 by Republic Records,<ref name=\":1\" /> less than six months after ''Sweetener'', which was released in August 2018. On releasing the album so soon after her previous offering, Grande said \"my dream has always been to be \u2014 obviously not a rapper, but, like, to put out music in the way that a rapper does. I feel like there are certain standards that pop women are held to that men aren't.\" Commenting on previous release strategies, she explained that \"we have to do the teaser before the single, then do the single, and wait to do the preorder, and radio has to impact before the video, and we have to do the discount on this day, and all this shit. It's just like, 'Bruh, I just want to fucking talk to my fans and sing and write music and drop it the way these boys do. Why do they get to make records like that and I don't?' So I do and I did and I am, and I will continue to.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/ariana-grande-new-release-strategy-thank-u-next-763458/|title=Ariana Grande Wants to Release Music Like a Rapper|website=Rolling Stone|date=5 December 2018|accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[album cover]] art, shot by Alfredo Flores, shows Grande laying upside-down on the floor with the album title painted on her neck. The digital edition cover features a pink border, whilst the physical edition features a black border.<ref name=\"iTunes\"/><ref name=\"Amazon\"/>\n\n===Tour===\n{{main|Sweetener World Tour}}On October 25, 2018, Grande officially announced the [[Sweetener World Tour]], in promotion of both ''Thank U, Next'' and [[Sweetener (album)|''Sweetener'']] (2018).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/10/25/ariana-grande-sweetener-world-tour|title=Ariana Grande announces Sweetener World Tour|last=Hussein|first=Wandera|date=October 25, 2018|website=The Fader|access-date=October 26, 2018}}</ref> The tour began on March 18, 2019, with the first leg consisting of 53 shows across North America.<ref name=\"billboarddates\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8481638/ariana-grande-sweetener-tour-dates|title=Ariana Grande Announces 'Sweetener' World Tour: See the Dates|work=Billboard|access-date=October 25, 2018}}</ref> The second leg of the tour began on August 17, 2019, consisting of 28 shows across Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/1073652982149996544|title=EUROPE|last=Grande|first=Ariana|date=December 14, 2018|website=Twitter|accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref> [[Normani]] and Social House were announced as the opening acts for the first leg of the tour.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8483187/normani-joins-ariana-grande-sweetener-world-tour|title=Normani to Join Ariana Grande as Support For Sweetener World Tour|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==Singles==\nThe [[Thank U, Next (song)|title track]] was released as the [[lead single]] from the album on November 3, 2018 without prior announcements.<ref name=\"TUN USA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2018/11/04/ariana-grandes-thank-u-next-single-pete-davidson-mac-miller/1882680002/|title=Ariana Grande says her exes heard 'Thank U, Next' before its release|last=McDermott|first=Maeve|date=November 4, 2018|website=USA Today|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Ivie|first=Devon|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/11/ariana-grande-teases-post-pete-davidson-album-thank-u-next.html|title=Ariana Grande Is Hyping Up Her Next Album, Thank U, Next|work=Vulture|date=November 3, 2018|accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref> Commercially, the single was a massive success, peaking at number-one of the charts of 12 countries and breaking a string of records, including the record for the most plays in a single day by a female artist on [[Spotify]]. The song also became Grande's first number-one single on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. She performed the song on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' on November 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-ellen-752968/|title=See Ariana Grande Debut Live 'Thank U, Next' on 'Ellen'|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=November 7, 2018|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=January 13, 2019}}</ref> Its [[Thank U, Next (song)#Music video|accompanying music video]] was released on November 30, which broke the records for both [[List of most-viewed online videos in the first 24 hours|the most-watched music video in YouTube within 24 hours]] and the fastest [[Vevo]] video to reach 100 million views on YouTube.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8488652/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-biggest-music-video-debut-youtube|title=Ariana Grande's 'Thank U, Next' Has the Biggest Music Video Debut in YouTube History|last=Engelman|first=Nicole|date=December 4, 2018|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-music-ariana-grande-idUSKBN1O32FZ|title=Grande's 'thank u, next' bests Adele to fastest 100 million views|date=December 4, 2018|agency=Reuters|accessdate=December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n\"[[7 Rings]]\" was released as the second single on January 18, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Squires|first=Bethy|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/ariana-grande-reveals-the-backstory-for-7-rings.html|title=Ariana Grande's Next Single Will Be About That Time She Got Drunk and Bought All Her Friends Rings|date=January 10, 2019|accessdate=January 13, 2019|work=Vulture}}</ref>  The track was also commercially successful, peaking atop of the charts of 15 countries, including the US, debuting atop of the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making Grande the third female artist to have two or more songs debuting at the top slot of the Hot 100. This also made Grande the third artist in history to have an album with two songs that debuted at number one on the Hot 100, after Drake's ''[[Scorpion (Drake album)|Scorpion]]'' in 2018 and Mariah Carey's ''[[Daydream (Mariah Carey album)|Daydream]]'' in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8495899/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-album-historic-chart-company|title=Ariana Grande's 'Thank U, Next' Album Is in Historic Chart Company, Before Its Release|work=Billboard|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=January 31, 2019}}</ref> \"7 Rings\" also broke the record for the most streamed song in 24 hours on Spotify, receiving 14.9 million streams globally.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/ariana-grande/news/ariana-grande-breaks-her-own-record-again-with-7-rings|title=Ariana Grande breaks her own record (again) with '7 Rings'|date=January 19, 2019|website=[[MTV]] UK|access-date=January 19, 2019}}</ref> It received generally mixed reviews from music critics,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/ariana-grande-7-rings-thank-u-next-780799/|title=Song You Need to Know: Ariana Grande, '7 Rings'|last=Spanos|first=Brittany|date=January 25, 2019|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/ariana-grande-7-rings/|title=Ariana Grande '7 rings'|last=Cox|first=Jamieson|date=January 18, 2019|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Kornhaber\">{{cite web |last=Kornhaber |first=Spencer |title=How Ariana Grande Fell Off the Cultural-Appropriation Tightrope |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/01/ariana-grandes-7-rings-really-cultural-appropriation/580978/ |website=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |date=January 23, 2019}}</ref> and was the center of plagiarism accusations from multiple artists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8494108/princess-nokia-ariana-grande-7-rings|title=Princess Nokia Accuses Ariana Grande of Stealing Her Sound on '7 Rings'|work=Billboard}}</ref><ref name=\"PN\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/princess-nokia-accuses-ariana-grande-of-copying-her-on-new-song-7-rings/|title=Princess Nokia Accuses Ariana Grande of Copying Her on New Song '7 rings'|last=Straus|first=Matthew|date=January 18, 2019|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/soulja-boy-princess-nokia-ariana-grande-copied-7-rings.html|title=Just How Many Artists Feel They Got Ripped Off by Ariana Grande?|work=Vulture}}</ref> \"7 Rings\" was also nominated for [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] at the [[62nd Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/music/news/2020-grammys-nominations-list-1203410085/|title=Grammy Awards Nominations: The Complete List|author=Variety Staff|date=2019-11-20|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Break Up with Your Girlfriend, I'm Bored]]\" was released as the third single on February 8, 2019, the same day the album was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ArianaGrande.lnk.to/breakup|title=Break Up with Your Girlfriend, I'm Bored|website=|accessdate=February 9, 2019}}</ref> The song debuted atop of the charts in Ireland and the United Kingdom. In the latter, Grande became the first female artist to replace herself at number one on the chart, and joined only three other artists in having three chart-topping singles in under 100 days.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ariana-grande-scores-a-record-breaking-week-with-thank-u-next-on-the-official-chart__25567/|title=Ariana Grande scores a record-breaking week with Thank U, Next on the Official Chart|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=February 15, 2019|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref> As the track became her fifth number-one single in Ireland, Grande now also holds the record for the most number ones in the 2010s decade on the chart, alongside [[Rihanna]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/ariana-grande-claims-the-official-irish-chart-double-as-break-up-with-your-girlfriend-im-bored-and-thank-u-next-debut-at-number-1__25568/|title=Ariana Grande claims the Official Irish Chart Double as Break Up With Your Girlfriend, I'm Bored and Thank U, Next debut at Number 1|last=White|first=Jack|date=February 15, 2019|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref> \"Break Up with Your Girlfriend, I'm Bored\" debuted at number two on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming Grande's 13th top ten single on the chart. With this single at number two, \"7 Rings\" at number one and \"Thank U, Next\" at number three, Grande became the first artist to monopolize the top three on the chart since [[The Beatles]] in 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8498841/ariana-grande-top-3-spots-hot-100|title=Ariana Grande Claims Nos. 1, 2 & 3 on Billboard Hot 100, Is First Act to Achieve the Feat Since The Beatles in 1964|last=Trust|first=Gary|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Promotional single===\n\"[[Imagine (Ariana Grande song)|Imagine]]\" was released as the album's promotional single on December 14, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8489864/ariana-grande-countdown-next-single-imagine|title=Ariana Grande Drops Countdown For Her Next Single, 'Imagine'|work=Billboard|last=Aniftos|first=Rania|date=December 11, 2018|accessdate=December 12, 2018}}</ref> Grande performed the song on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'' on December 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8490967/ariana-grande-performs-imagine-on-fallon|title=Ariana Grande Got Into the Christmas Spirit for Her TV Debut Performance of 'Imagine': Watch|website=Billboard|date=December 19, 2018|accessdate=December 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 8.1/10<ref name=\"AnyDecentMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/9724/Ariana-Grande-thank-u-next.aspx|title=thank u, next by Ariana Grande reviews|work=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n| MC = 86/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/thank-u-next/ariana-grande|title=thank u, next by Ariana Grande Reviews and Tracks|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/thank-u-next-mw0003246119|title=thank u, next \u2013 Ariana Grande|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/ariana-grande-has-no-fucks-to-spare-on-the-thrilling-th-1832533748|title=\nAriana Grande has no fucks to spare on the thrilling Thank U, Next|last=Zaleski|first=Annie|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Consequence Of Sound]]''\n| rev3score = A-<ref>https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/02/album-review-ariana-grande-thank-u-next/</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev4score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-review-presenting-pop-queen-unashamedly/|title=Ariana Grande, Thank U, Next review: presenting the pop queen at her most unashamedly honest|last=White|first=Adam|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=February 8, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev5score = B+<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/music-reviews/2019/02/11/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-review/|title=Ariana Grande reminds listeners who's in charge on intimate ''thank u, next'': EW review|last=Johnston|first=Maura|authorlink=Maura Johnston|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/feb/08/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-review|title=Ariana Grande: Thank U, Next review \u2013 a break-up album of wit and wonder|last=Cragg|first=Michael|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=February 8, 2019|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev7score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-review-new-album-stream-pete-davidson-mac-miller-grammys-a8769931.html|title=Ariana Grande, thank u next review: Pop star owns her contradictions and embraces her inner mean girl|newspaper=The Independent|last=Brown|first=Helen|date=February 8, 2019|accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Irish Times]]''\n| rev8score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"theirishtimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-review-pop-superstar-at-her-defiant-brilliant-best-1.3786894|title=Ariana Grande: Thank U, Next review \u2013 Pop superstar at her defiant, brilliant best|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]|last=Power|first=Ed|date=February 8, 2019|accessdate=March 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-review-2-2446734|title=Ariana Grande \u2013 'Thank U, Next' review|work=[[NME]]|last=Daly|first=Rhian|date=February 12, 2019|accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev10score = 7.9/10<ref name=\"pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/ariana-grande-thank-u-next/|title=Ariana Grande: thank u, next|work=Pitchfork|last=Kameir|first=Rawiya|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev11 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev11score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"RollingStone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-album-review-793887/|title=Review: Ariana Grande Moves on in Spectacular Style With \u2018Thank U, Next\u2019|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Sheffield|date=February 12, 2019|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\nUpon release, ''Thank U, Next'' received widespread acclaim from music critics, with many praising its cohesiveness and production. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received a weighted average score of 86, based on 24 reviews, indicating \"critical acclaim\". The metascore is the highest of Grande's career.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\n[[Rob Sheffield]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' stated that ''Thank U, Next'' is \"one of the year's best pop albums so far, even in a 2019 that's already turning out to be a great one for new music. ''Thank U, Next'' makes you suspect that the best Ariana is yet to come.\"<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/> Ross Horton from ''[[The Line of Best Fit]]'' praised both the songwriting and production of the album, stating that it is an \"airtight, dense pop record with an obnoxiously brash production\" and commenting that \"even the most delicate, sensual things here are tightly compressed and scrubbed of anything resembling acoustics.\"<ref name=\"TLOBF\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/reviews/albums/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-album-review|title=Ariana Grande's Thank U, Next is her greatest record yet|last=Horton|first=Ross|date=February 8, 2019|website=[[The Line of Best Fit]]|access-date=February 8, 2019}}</ref> [[AllMusic]]'s [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] also gave the album a positive review, commenting that \"Grande is swaggering with [...] confidence\" and concluding that the album \"embodies every aspect of Ariana Grande, the grand pop star.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Mikael Wood of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said, \"''Thank U, Next'' flaunts Grande's emotional healing; it's suffused with the joy of discovering that what didn't kill her really did make her stronger.\"<ref name=\"L.A. Times\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-ariana-grande-thank-u-next-grammys-20190208-story.html|title=Review: Ariana Grande's 'Thank U, Next' swagger upstages Grammys drama|last=Wood|first=Mikael|date=February 8, 2019|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMichael Cragg of ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented that ''Thank U, Next'' seems to be a \"result of a burst of creativity and a prevailing mood\", yet criticized \"[[7 Rings]]\" as a \"braggadocious, ice-cold low point\" of the album. He concluded positively, stating that Grande is a \"pop star [...] finally working out who they are and what they want to say\" and compared the album to [[Rihanna]]'s [[Anti (album)|''Anti'']].<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Helen Brown from ''[[The Independent]]'' stated that that Grande is \"embracing her inner mean girl (on the sexy \"[[Break Up with Your Girlfriend, I'm Bored]]\") [and] owning her flaws and contradictions\" on tracks such as \"Needy\" and \"[[NASA (Ariana Grande song)|NASA]]\", yet concluded that the album lacks enough \"vocal grit\".<ref name=\"Independent\"/> Sal Cinquemani from ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' awarded the album three-and-a-half stars out of five, believing that the album \"is easily Grande's most sonically consistent effort to date\". He criticized that \"some of the [...] tracks tend to blur together\", but ultimately concluded in saying that Grande's \"refusal to fake a smile that proves to be what makes her so damn likeable.\"<ref name=\"Slant\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review-ariana-grande-embraces-her-flaws-on-thank-u-next/|title=Review: Ariana Grande Embraces Her Flaws on ''Thank U, Next'' |last=Cinquemani |first=Sal |date=February 8, 2019 |website=Slant Magazine |access-date=February 8, 2019}}</ref> In a [[capsule review]] for ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', [[Robert Christgau]] gave the album a three-star honorable mention ({{Rating-Christgau|hm3}}) and summed it up as Grande's \"maturing from [[multitrack recording|multitracked]] studio trickeration to straight love songs\u2014love songs an old grouch might complain are all too superstar-specific\"; the title track and \"Ghostin'\" were cited as highlights.<ref name=\"Vice\">{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/vbwkxd/robert-christgau-on-ariana-grandes-garden-of-sonic-delights|title=Robert Christgau on Ariana Grande's Garden of Sonic Delights|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=March 23, 2019|accessdate=March 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Thank U, Next'' was named as one of the best albums of 2019. ''[[MTV]]'' named it as one of the ten albums of 2019, stating that the album \"unpacks love, lust, and pain in a metallic pop coating. It's cooler, weirder, and deeper than ''[[Sweetener (album)|Sweetener]]'', and manages to make that project look shockingly surface-level\".<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3147968/ariana-grande-thank-u-next-albums-of-the-year/|title=ALBUMS OF THE YEAR: ARIANA GRANDE\u2019S THANK U, NEXT WAS THE RAINBOW AT THE END OF HER SHITSTORM|work=[[MTV]]|last=Roth|first=Madeline|date=December 16, 2019|accessdate=January 15, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' ranked ''Thank U, Next'' as their number best album of 2019, stating that \"the pop princess officially became a queen\".<ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2019: Staff Picks |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8545657/best-albums-of-2019-top-50 |website=Billboard |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\nThis was also the second consecutive year that ''Billboard'' ranked Grande's album as the best of year after naming the artist's previous album, ''Sweetener'', as their number one best album of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=50 Best Albums of 2018: Critics' Picks |url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/8489227/best-albums-2018-staff-picks |website=Billboard |accessdate=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+Awards\n|-\n! Year\n! Organization\n! Award\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"row\" | 2019\n|[[People's Choice Awards]]\n|Album of 2019\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/09/e-peoples-choice-awards-finalists-complete-list-1202710461/|title=E! People\u2019s Choice Awards Finalists Announced; Voting Open Through Oct. 18 \u2013 Complete List|last=Evans|first=Greg|date=2019-09-04|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[American Music Awards]]\n|[[American Music Award for Favorite Pop/Rock Album|Favorite Pop/Rock Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theamas.com/2019/10/the-american-music-awards-announces-2019-nominees/|title=The American Music Awards Announces 2019 Nominees|date=2019-10-24|website=American Music Awards|language=en|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref>\n|-\n|!scope=\"row\"| [[LOS40 Music Awards]]\n| [[Premios 40 Principales for Best International Album|Best International Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://los40.com/los40/2019/09/12/radio/1568271871_802645.html |title=JONAS BROTHERS, ROSAL\u00cdA, AITANA, LEIVA Y MANUEL CARRASCO, M\u00c1XIMOS NOMINADOS DE LOS40 MUSIC AWARDS 2019|work=Los40.com|access-date=September 13, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"row\" | 2020\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Grammy Award]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/2020-grammy-awards-complete-nominees-list|title=2020 GRAMMY Awards: Complete Nominees List|date=2019-11-18|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Juno Award]]s\n| [[Juno Award for International Album of the Year|International Album of the Year]]\n| {{pending}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://junoawards.ca/2020-juno-award-nominees/|title=2020 Juno Awards: Complete Nominees List|date=January 2020|website=junoawards.ca|language=en|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|+Year-end and decade-end lists\n|-\n! Publication\n! Accolade\n! Rank\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| ''[[Afisha|Afisha Daily]]'' (Russia)\n| The Best Foreign Albums of 2019\n| {{center|17}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://daily.afisha.ru/music/13948-luchshie-zarubezhnye-albomy-2019-goda/|trans-title=The Best Foreign Albums of 2019|title=\u041b\u0443\u0447\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0436\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0430\u043b\u044c\u0431\u043e\u043c\u044b 2019 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430|website=[[Afisha|Afisha Daily]]|date=December 26, 2019}}</ref>}}\n|-\n|''[[AllMusic]]''\n| Best of 2019\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/year-in-review/2019|title=AllMusic Best of 2019 {{!}} AllMusic 2019 in Review|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref>}}\n|-\n|''[[Associated Press]]''\n| AP's Top Albums of 2019\n| {{center|7}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/9729986d3533f1a14f79d6595183cd46|title=AP\u2019s top albums of 2019: Ari Lennox, Summer Walker, Anitta|date=2019-12-06|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>}}\n|-\n|''[[BBC News|BBC]]''\n| Top 10 Albums of 2019\n| {{center|8}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-50824726|title=The best albums and songs of 2019 revealed|last=Savage|first=Mark|date=2019-12-21|access-date=2019-12-21|language=en-GB}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2019\n| {{center|1}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8545657/best-albums-of-2019-top-50|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2019: Staff Picks|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| The 100 Greatest Albums of the 2010s\n| {{center|8}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/8543722/best-albums-of-the-2010s-top-100|title=The 100 Greatest Albums of the 2010s: Staff Picks|website=Billboard|access